00:01:29.090 --> 00:01:31.460
How presumptuous must
you be to think that you

00:01:31.460 --> 00:01:33.580
can talk about these things?

00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:38.020
So I want to get the
disclaimer right on the board

00:01:38.020 --> 00:01:40.610
right away, which is
that I do not know

00:01:40.610 --> 00:01:42.084
what the origin of life is.

00:01:42.084 --> 00:01:44.125
I do not know what the
origin of the universe is.

00:01:44.125 --> 00:01:46.420
I do not know the
meaning of life.

00:01:46.420 --> 00:01:48.310
What I do think is
that we have a way

00:01:48.310 --> 00:01:51.290
of talking about
these things now

00:01:51.290 --> 00:01:53.250
that is sort of better
than we had before,

00:01:53.250 --> 00:01:55.800
if before I means 500 years ago.

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:58.460
And so this is not so
much a set of answers

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:01.090
to difficult questions
as it is encouragement

00:02:01.090 --> 00:02:04.080
to continue the conversation
within a particular framework.

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:07.200
And I'd like to start by telling
you the story of Lucia de Berk.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:09.250
She was a Dutch nurse.

00:02:09.250 --> 00:02:13.870
In 2004, she was convicted to
a sentence of life imprisonment

00:02:13.870 --> 00:02:17.180
for murdering several
infants under her care.

00:02:17.180 --> 00:02:18.860
Now this is a sad story.

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:21.340
But if you look into it,
there is an interesting thing

00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:23.690
about the legal
proceedings, which

00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:27.460
is there essentially wasn't
any evidence she had done it.

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:29.660
And you might ask,
how is it possible

00:02:29.660 --> 00:02:33.920
that someone gets convicted of
basically being a mass murder

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:35.120
without any direct evidence?

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:36.578
There were no
eyewitnesses that saw

00:02:36.578 --> 00:02:39.150
her do anything, no
poison in her handbag

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:40.560
or anything like that.

00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:43.270
And the answer is mathematics.

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:46.870
The prosecution
asked statisticians

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:50.910
to estimate the likelihood
that this number of children

00:02:50.910 --> 00:02:53.120
would die when a certain
nurse was on duty.

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:55.080
And they said oh, it's
one in a million chance

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:57.090
or hundreds of
millions of chance.

00:02:57.090 --> 00:03:00.750
That was the primary reason
why she was convicted.

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:03.230
Now later, other
mathematicians looked at it

00:03:03.230 --> 00:03:06.540
and realize that it had
been bad mathematics.

00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:09.815
The argument was it was
more like a one in 25 or one

00:03:09.815 --> 00:03:12.240
in 100 chance that something
like that would happen,

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:14.720
which as I'm sure you all
know, those chances happen

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:15.910
all the time.

00:03:15.910 --> 00:03:18.570
In fact someone pointed
out that the total death

00:03:18.570 --> 00:03:20.810
rate for children in
this hospital-- I mean,

00:03:20.810 --> 00:03:23.880
it's a pediatric care hospital,
there's sick children there--

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:26.825
the death rate went down
after she was hired,

00:03:26.825 --> 00:03:28.200
which is not the
effect you would

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:32.580
expect as the hiring of a
serial killer to really have.

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:36.160
But the other question is,
besides the bad mathematics,

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:40.437
why were the people on
the jury so easily swayed,

00:03:40.437 --> 00:03:43.020
even though there was no direct
evidence that she had actually

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:44.020
done it?

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:45.840
And I'd like to point
to the possibility

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:49.170
that really it was part
of our very human desire

00:03:49.170 --> 00:03:52.670
to blame something
when something happens.

00:03:52.670 --> 00:03:55.090
Rather than to think that
just things happen and there's

00:03:55.090 --> 00:03:57.970
a little bit of irrationality
and randomness in the world,

00:03:57.970 --> 00:04:02.010
we like to think there's a
reason why things happen.

00:04:02.010 --> 00:04:03.980
So when a whole bunch
of children die,

00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:07.470
more than we might expect,
we want someone to blame.

00:04:07.470 --> 00:04:10.846
And once that starts,
we convince ourselves

00:04:10.846 --> 00:04:12.470
that we are on the
right track, finding

00:04:12.470 --> 00:04:14.270
this reason for this happening.

00:04:14.270 --> 00:04:16.540
The picture on the left is
what Lucia de Berk actually

00:04:16.540 --> 00:04:17.610
looks like.

00:04:17.610 --> 00:04:20.140
The picture on the right
is the courtroom sketch

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:21.320
of what she looks like.

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:25.100
Once you decide that this
person is the evil one who

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:28.230
was responsible for this,
then you look at her

00:04:28.230 --> 00:04:29.670
in a slightly different way.

00:04:29.670 --> 00:04:31.970
Fortunately the
bad math went away.

00:04:31.970 --> 00:04:34.060
The good math took over
and she was released,

00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:38.030
she was exonerated, and
found innocent later on.

00:04:38.030 --> 00:04:41.660
But the idea that we find
reasons why things happen

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:43.300
is not necessarily a bad one.

00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:44.810
It's an ancient one
and it goes back

00:04:44.810 --> 00:04:47.820
to some of the greatest
thinkers in history.

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:49.870
Aristotle very
famously had what he

00:04:49.870 --> 00:04:51.677
called the four
causes for things

00:04:51.677 --> 00:04:53.260
happening, which we
might really think

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:57.220
of as four kinds of
explanation why things occur.

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:00.080
And one of them was the
final cause for something.

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:04.630
The final cause for Aristotle is
the reason for which something

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:08.730
exists, the goal for which it
is created in the first place.

00:05:08.730 --> 00:05:13.770
The final cause of a seed is to
grow into a tree, for example.

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:16.530
And this kind of reasoning,
this kind of metaphysical view

00:05:16.530 --> 00:05:19.060
that the world at
its deepest levels

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:21.800
is a story of
causes and effects,

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:23.340
went through to these guys.

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:25.900
This is Spinoza and
Leibniz, Baruch Spinoza

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:27.770
and Gottfried Leibniz.

00:05:27.770 --> 00:05:30.160
And they promulgated something
we call the principle

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:32.040
of sufficient reason.

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:33.850
They also promulgated
a principle

00:05:33.850 --> 00:05:36.940
that philosophers' hair gets
better and better over time,

00:05:36.940 --> 00:05:37.890
as you see.

00:05:37.890 --> 00:05:40.040
I think Leibniz got
artificial help.

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:42.820
But overall, there's
certainly a progress in nature

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:44.630
that we can observe here.

00:05:44.630 --> 00:05:46.070
The principal of
sufficient reason

00:05:46.070 --> 00:05:48.460
is simply the statement
that everything

00:05:48.460 --> 00:05:49.970
happens for a reason.

00:05:49.970 --> 00:05:52.600
You can find this on bumper
stickers and greeting cards,

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:54.890
but Leibniz in
particular raised it

00:05:54.890 --> 00:05:57.000
to the level of a
metaphysical principle.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:02.030
For everything that happens,
there is a cause or reason why.

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:03.190
And again it's not crazy.

00:06:03.190 --> 00:06:06.260
In our everyday experience,
that is kind of what we see.

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:08.140
Things do not just happen.

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:11.370
The book is not going to
see just fly off into air.

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:13.580
There seems to be reasons
why things happen.

00:06:13.580 --> 00:06:16.680
If the book moves, it's
because I moved it.

00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:19.130
And for Aristotle and
for many other people,

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:22.590
this metaphysical claim
that things that happen

00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:25.540
do so because something
causes them to happen,

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:28.150
influenced their
ideas about physics.

00:06:28.150 --> 00:06:31.380
So for Aristotle, if
things are moving,

00:06:31.380 --> 00:06:33.750
it implies that
something is moving them.

00:06:33.750 --> 00:06:35.990
There is a reason why
things are moving.

00:06:35.990 --> 00:06:38.690
And his reasoning is
quite straightforward.

00:06:38.690 --> 00:06:41.040
If I start pushing on
the book, it will move.

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:43.390
And if I stop, it stops.

00:06:43.390 --> 00:06:44.100
There you go.

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:47.410
That's the basis for a way
of thinking about physics,

00:06:47.410 --> 00:06:49.720
that if you see things
moving in the world,

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:51.000
you need to explain that.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.320
You need to find the reason
why, what the mover is.

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:57.520
And this extends from
individual objects like books

00:06:57.520 --> 00:06:59.120
to everything in the universe.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:01.810
The universe is full of motions.

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:04.540
But to Aristotle, the
natural state of being

00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:07.090
was for things to
stay stationary.

00:07:07.090 --> 00:07:10.160
So the existence of all these
motions and transformations

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:12.310
of all sorts
implies that there's

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:17.350
something behind the scenes
causing those kinds of motions.

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:21.700
That is not how we think about
fundamental physics today.

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:24.805
Over the course of improved
explanation and experimentation

00:07:24.805 --> 00:07:28.690
and theorizing, we have a
very, very different way

00:07:28.690 --> 00:07:30.280
of thinking about
how the world works

00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:32.250
at its most fundamental level.

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:34.350
But it's not a way that
we make a big deal of.

00:07:34.350 --> 00:07:37.760
There's many things that
popularization of science

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:39.757
will talk about
over and over again.

00:07:39.757 --> 00:07:41.590
You can't go faster
than the speed of light.

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:45.480
You can't know your position
and velocity at the same time.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:48.710
But we don't talk about the
fact that the whole principle

00:07:48.710 --> 00:07:51.040
of cause and effect as
a fundamental organizing

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:54.910
principle for the universe
is no longer part of our best

00:07:54.910 --> 00:07:56.284
theories of physics.

00:07:56.284 --> 00:07:57.450
Some people talked about it.

00:07:57.450 --> 00:07:59.670
Bertrand Russell
liked to emphasize it.

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:02.337
He was primarily a philosopher,
but a mathematical philosopher

00:08:02.337 --> 00:08:03.420
who knew a lot of physics.

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:06.300
And he said, "The law
of causality I believe,

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:08.510
like much that passes
muster among philosophers,

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:13.016
is a relic of a bygone age,
surviving, like the monarchy--"

00:08:13.016 --> 00:08:14.390
he just had to
get that in there.

00:08:14.390 --> 00:08:16.880
He couldn't stick to just
the philosophy and science--

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:21.140
"only because it is erroneously
supposed to do no harm."

00:08:21.140 --> 00:08:24.180
So this should be, I
hope, in your minds,

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:26.980
quite an extraordinary claim.

00:08:26.980 --> 00:08:30.440
The law of causality, that you
have a cause for every effect,

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:32.789
that the cause precedes
the effect, that's

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:35.340
not part of our understanding
of the world anymore.

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:37.419
What is going on?

00:08:37.419 --> 00:08:40.008
Well it's not that
anything could happen.

00:08:40.008 --> 00:08:42.049
It's not that because
there's no cause and effect

00:08:42.049 --> 00:08:44.049
at the deep level, the
book can in fact just fly

00:08:44.049 --> 00:08:45.690
all over the place.

00:08:45.690 --> 00:08:48.360
The point is that we've
replaced the principal that

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:51.100
causes precede effects
with a principle

00:08:51.100 --> 00:08:53.550
that the world is
governed by patterns.

00:08:53.550 --> 00:08:55.740
And this happened slowly.

00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:58.689
Here's one example, sort
of the tipping point,

00:08:58.689 --> 00:09:00.230
if you will, from
one way of thinking

00:09:00.230 --> 00:09:02.600
about the world to another
one, was the principal we

00:09:02.600 --> 00:09:04.860
call conservation of momentum.

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:08.339
If any of you in the room
have taken physics classes,

00:09:08.339 --> 00:09:10.630
you have been tortured by
the principle of conservation

00:09:10.630 --> 00:09:12.960
of momentum to sort of
find the solution when

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:15.790
different balls bump into
each other and so forth.

00:09:15.790 --> 00:09:18.330
But in fact this
principle is part

00:09:18.330 --> 00:09:20.060
of a whole new way
of thinking about how

00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:22.000
reality works at a deep level.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.355
It took hundreds of years
and many, many smart people

00:09:24.355 --> 00:09:24.980
to think of it.

00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:27.610
One of the primary
people was Ibn Sina,

00:09:27.610 --> 00:09:29.970
who was a Persian polymath.

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:31.970
To a modern physicist
like me, Ibn Sina

00:09:31.970 --> 00:09:35.510
is extremely annoying, because
he wasn't even a physicist,

00:09:35.510 --> 00:09:36.650
primarily.

00:09:36.650 --> 00:09:37.450
He was a doctor.

00:09:37.450 --> 00:09:38.450
He was a medical doctor.

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:40.449
He wrote a lot about the
human body and anatomy.

00:09:40.449 --> 00:09:42.670
He did physics in
his spare time,

00:09:42.670 --> 00:09:44.570
and he invented
conservation of momentum.

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:46.945
This is very annoying to me.

00:09:46.945 --> 00:09:49.070
But he wouldn't have said
conservation of momentum.

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:51.730
Again, it took hundreds
of years to get it right.

00:09:51.730 --> 00:09:55.840
The basic idea that Ibn
Sina put his finger on

00:09:55.840 --> 00:09:58.252
is that if you could
remove friction,

00:09:58.252 --> 00:10:01.680
if you could remove dissipation,
if you imagine something

00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:05.810
moving through the vacuum,
it would keep moving forever.

00:10:05.810 --> 00:10:08.374
This was the invention
of that other device

00:10:08.374 --> 00:10:10.540
that physics teachers like
to use to torture people,

00:10:10.540 --> 00:10:12.510
the frictionless surface.

00:10:12.510 --> 00:10:15.040
If you imagine something
moving in the complete absence

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:16.850
of friction, it
would not slow down

00:10:16.850 --> 00:10:18.380
or require a cause
to keep moving,

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:20.570
it would just keep moving.

00:10:20.570 --> 00:10:23.440
And this principle was improved
upon by people like Galileo who

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:25.950
did experiments, and
finally Christiaan Huygens

00:10:25.950 --> 00:10:27.580
was the one who
actually formulated

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:32.080
our modern mathematical notion
of conservation of momentum.

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:34.390
So why is conservation of
momentum such a big deal,

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:35.890
over and above
the fact that it's

00:10:35.890 --> 00:10:37.900
a tool for physicists to use?

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:40.290
Because it implies that
there's a different way

00:10:40.290 --> 00:10:43.380
that the world naturally is.

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:46.150
If you're Aristotle, the
natural way for things to be

00:10:46.150 --> 00:10:49.380
is to kind of sit there
in their happy place,

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:52.540
and you need to do something
to get them moving.

00:10:52.540 --> 00:10:54.680
In a world with
conservation of momentum,

00:10:54.680 --> 00:10:58.590
the natural thing for the
world is to move and change,

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:01.780
and implies you don't need to
explain why things are moving.

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:03.922
Things just naturally move.

00:11:03.922 --> 00:11:06.130
And this was developed over
time and probably reached

00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:10.375
the pinnacle with Pierre-Simon
Laplace, a French mathematician

00:11:10.375 --> 00:11:12.882
and physicist around
the year 1800.

00:11:12.882 --> 00:11:14.465
He did not invent
classical mechanics.

00:11:14.465 --> 00:11:17.080
It was Newton, as we all know,
who really put the finishing

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:18.720
touches on classical mechanics.

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:20.960
But you can make the
argument that Laplace

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:24.090
was the first person to really
internalize what it meant,

00:11:24.090 --> 00:11:27.540
the deep implications of this
Newtonian clockwork universe

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:28.816
worldview.

00:11:28.816 --> 00:11:30.690
So you know that if you
do a physics problem,

00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:32.890
and again you ignore
friction and dissipation

00:11:32.890 --> 00:11:35.510
and so forth, you play
physics billiards,

00:11:35.510 --> 00:11:38.800
physicist billiards where
balls just bump into each other

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:42.920
and so forth, you can solve
the problem of these two balls

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:44.490
are moving with
certain velocities.

00:11:44.490 --> 00:11:46.573
They scatter and they go
off in another direction.

00:11:46.573 --> 00:11:48.230
What is the direction
and the speed

00:11:48.230 --> 00:11:50.500
at which the balls
are going to go?

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:52.970
Laplace was the
first to point out

00:11:52.970 --> 00:11:54.975
that that process is reversible.

00:11:54.975 --> 00:11:56.900
That if you started
up here saying

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:59.040
that the balls are
moving apart, what

00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:01.390
were they doing in the past?

00:12:01.390 --> 00:12:04.430
And Newton's laws make an
absolutely clear prediction

00:12:04.430 --> 00:12:06.450
for what they were
doing in this world

00:12:06.450 --> 00:12:08.720
where you can ignore
friction and dissipation.

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:11.310
If you made a movie
of this whole process

00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:15.600
and played it backward, it
would look completely plausible.

00:12:15.600 --> 00:12:19.560
So Laplace invented what we
now call Laplace's demon,

00:12:19.560 --> 00:12:22.000
or what he called
a vast intellect.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.550
Laplace's demon
is something that

00:12:23.550 --> 00:12:25.895
has the ability-- what
we'd now really call

00:12:25.895 --> 00:12:27.640
it is a really good computer.

00:12:27.640 --> 00:12:30.720
Maybe you have a Laplace's demon
in one of the other buildings.

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:33.180
If Laplace's demon
knew everything

00:12:33.180 --> 00:12:36.560
about the state of the
universe at one moment in time,

00:12:36.560 --> 00:12:39.490
the position and the momentum
of every particle moving

00:12:39.490 --> 00:12:42.000
in the universe,
then Laplace says

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.350
that vast intellect would
know the future and past just

00:12:45.350 --> 00:12:46.905
as surely as the present.

00:12:46.905 --> 00:12:49.180
If that vast intellect knew
all the laws of physics

00:12:49.180 --> 00:12:51.320
and was able to calculate
what would happen,

00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:52.695
there would be
nothing that would

00:12:52.695 --> 00:12:55.230
be uncertain to that
intellect about what

00:12:55.230 --> 00:12:58.500
would happen in the future,
what had happened in the past.

00:12:58.500 --> 00:13:01.490
So this is, even though
it's a subtle difference,

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:04.460
a crucially different way
of thinking about the world.

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:08.700
It's not that this configuration
of stuff causes this one

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:10.350
and therefore causes that.

00:13:10.350 --> 00:13:13.110
All of them are
related by a pattern

00:13:13.110 --> 00:13:14.710
called the laws of physics.

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:19.560
Just like the integers 0, 1, 2,
3, minus 1, minus 2, minus 3,

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:22.670
the number two happens
after the number one

00:13:22.670 --> 00:13:24.570
and before the
number three, but we

00:13:24.570 --> 00:13:27.610
don't say that the number one
is the cause of number two,

00:13:27.610 --> 00:13:29.580
or two is the cause of three.

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:32.110
We just say that every
number is one bigger or less

00:13:32.110 --> 00:13:33.640
than the numbers next to it.

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:35.960
It's just a pattern
that follows,

00:13:35.960 --> 00:13:38.650
and you can go forward
or backward equally well.

00:13:38.650 --> 00:13:40.460
And Laplace says that
is what the world is

00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:43.280
like at a deep level.

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:45.870
Now these things we know better
than Newtonian mechanics.

00:13:45.870 --> 00:13:48.140
We've had quantum mechanics,
statistical mechanics,

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:50.020
general relativity,
and so forth.

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:53.500
But the basic Laplacian
principle remains the same.

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:56.830
It's just the actual laws
that we have are different.

00:13:56.830 --> 00:13:59.020
So one of the claims
that I make in the book

00:13:59.020 --> 00:14:01.950
that I would like to defend
is that this audacious

00:14:01.950 --> 00:14:04.410
sounding idea, that
the laws of physics

00:14:04.410 --> 00:14:07.760
underlying everyday life
are completely known.

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:09.740
Now when I say this,
people like to stop

00:14:09.740 --> 00:14:11.900
listening when I say
underlying everyday life, so I

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:13.430
want to emphasize that.

00:14:13.430 --> 00:14:16.220
I'm not saying the laws of
physics are completely known.

00:14:16.220 --> 00:14:17.890
I'm not also saying
that everyday life

00:14:17.890 --> 00:14:18.800
is completely known.

00:14:18.800 --> 00:14:20.633
There's plenty of things
about everyday life

00:14:20.633 --> 00:14:23.190
that I don't know about,
plenty of things about physics

00:14:23.190 --> 00:14:25.210
we don't know about--
dark matter, dark energy,

00:14:25.210 --> 00:14:28.700
black holes, the Big Bang,
plenty of physics that is not

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:30.880
about the underlying
laws that we don't know--

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:32.960
high temperature,
superconductivity,

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:35.070
turbulence, and so forth.

00:14:35.070 --> 00:14:38.344
I'm making quite a specific
claim, that you and I

00:14:38.344 --> 00:14:40.010
and all this stuff
right in front of us,

00:14:40.010 --> 00:14:43.660
literally the stuff we can touch
and see in our everyday lives,

00:14:43.660 --> 00:14:47.110
these are made of things--
atoms, electrons, protons,

00:14:47.110 --> 00:14:48.310
neutrons.

00:14:48.310 --> 00:14:50.670
Those protons and neutrons
are made of quarks.

00:14:50.670 --> 00:14:52.930
And all these particles
interact in a certain way.

00:14:52.930 --> 00:14:56.360
And we know both what
those particles are

00:14:56.360 --> 00:14:58.410
and how they interact.

00:14:58.410 --> 00:15:01.120
When I say we know, not
only do we have a good idea,

00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:03.560
but a thousand years from now
or a million years from now

00:15:03.560 --> 00:15:05.960
this idea will still be right.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:07.800
Hopefully we will learn
more-- I mean, maybe

00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:09.959
the quarks and
electrons and so forth

00:15:09.959 --> 00:15:11.250
are made of even tinier things.

00:15:11.250 --> 00:15:12.620
That's great.

00:15:12.620 --> 00:15:15.650
But there won't stop being
quarks and electrons,

00:15:15.650 --> 00:15:17.990
and we won't be wrong
about how they interact.

00:15:17.990 --> 00:15:22.240
And there are deep reasons
for believing this is true.

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:24.280
Let me just tell you
what the ingredients are.

00:15:24.280 --> 00:15:25.700
This is an atom, right?

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:28.280
This a neutron and a
proton, an electron,

00:15:28.280 --> 00:15:31.150
so it's a deuterium
isotope of hydrogen.

00:15:31.150 --> 00:15:33.600
The electron is held
together to the nucleus

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:35.330
by electromagnetism.

00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:36.845
The individual
protons and neutrons

00:15:36.845 --> 00:15:39.470
are made of quarks, up and down
quarks, which are held together

00:15:39.470 --> 00:15:41.490
with the strong nuclear force.

00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:43.690
Occasionally an up
quark or a down quark

00:15:43.690 --> 00:15:46.820
can convert into the other
one by the weak nuclear force

00:15:46.820 --> 00:15:50.090
and give up a neutrino
in the process.

00:15:50.090 --> 00:15:53.220
Everything is pulled towards
everything else by gravity.

00:15:53.220 --> 00:15:56.840
And everything's swims in the
background of the Higgs field.

00:15:56.840 --> 00:15:58.570
The Higgs boson
particle is something

00:15:58.570 --> 00:16:01.985
we discovered just in 2012,
the Large Hadron Collider.

00:16:01.985 --> 00:16:03.360
The particle is
what happens when

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:06.100
you start this field
vibrating, but the field

00:16:06.100 --> 00:16:09.530
itself, the Higgs field
pervades all of space,

00:16:09.530 --> 00:16:11.530
affects the properties
of the other particles

00:16:11.530 --> 00:16:13.002
that we're made up.

00:16:13.002 --> 00:16:14.460
There are more
particles than this.

00:16:14.460 --> 00:16:16.900
These matter particles,
the electron, the quarks,

00:16:16.900 --> 00:16:19.557
neutrinos, they all
have heavier cousins.

00:16:19.557 --> 00:16:21.140
But they decay away
very, very quickly

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:22.140
if you try to make them.

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:24.150
They do not affect
our everyday lives.

00:16:24.150 --> 00:16:24.750
We know them.

00:16:24.750 --> 00:16:26.500
We can complete
them in the theory.

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:28.500
But you don't actually
need to know them to know

00:16:28.500 --> 00:16:30.640
what you and I are made out of.

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:35.050
So that's it, as far as our
everyday world is concerned.

00:16:35.050 --> 00:16:39.070
The point is that there's no
new particle, no new field,

00:16:39.070 --> 00:16:43.430
no new force that we
will ever discover

00:16:43.430 --> 00:16:47.460
that will have an impact on
our literal every day biology

00:16:47.460 --> 00:16:50.060
or environment, like
what holds this table up.

00:16:50.060 --> 00:16:52.220
We hope to discover
a lot more physics.

00:16:52.220 --> 00:16:55.630
It will not affect you or
what you're made out of.

00:16:55.630 --> 00:16:58.160
So I know this is
a-- I keep being

00:16:58.160 --> 00:17:00.360
told this is a technically
inclined audience.

00:17:00.360 --> 00:17:01.610
So you don't like the picture.

00:17:01.610 --> 00:17:03.080
The picture makes you nervous.

00:17:03.080 --> 00:17:04.270
You want an equation.

00:17:04.270 --> 00:17:07.210
So here it is.

00:17:07.210 --> 00:17:09.250
This is what Nobel
laureate Frank Wilczek

00:17:09.250 --> 00:17:11.160
has called the Core Theory.

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:13.690
And he invented the name to
emphasize that we usually

00:17:13.690 --> 00:17:17.380
distinguish between the standard
model of particle physics

00:17:17.380 --> 00:17:19.943
and general relativity,
our best theory of gravity.

00:17:19.943 --> 00:17:22.359
And the reason we do that is
because general relativity is

00:17:22.359 --> 00:17:24.829
a classical theory,
not a quantum theory.

00:17:24.829 --> 00:17:27.250
We don't have a full
and complete theory

00:17:27.250 --> 00:17:29.030
of quantum gravity yet.

00:17:29.030 --> 00:17:31.610
What gets lost in
that true statement

00:17:31.610 --> 00:17:33.530
is that we have a
pretty good every day

00:17:33.530 --> 00:17:35.620
theory of quantum gravity.

00:17:35.620 --> 00:17:38.815
We know quantum gravity in the
regime where fields are weak.

00:17:38.815 --> 00:17:41.230
We know quantum
gravity perfectly well

00:17:41.230 --> 00:17:43.650
if you want to use it to
calculate the Moon orbiting

00:17:43.650 --> 00:17:45.890
around the Earth, for example.

00:17:45.890 --> 00:17:47.640
So if you're literally
only interested

00:17:47.640 --> 00:17:52.850
in the regime of everyday life,
this is it, including gravity.

00:17:52.850 --> 00:17:56.600
This is basically the Feynman
path integral, the probability

00:17:56.600 --> 00:17:59.987
to go from one amplitude in a
field theory to another one.

00:17:59.987 --> 00:18:01.820
I'm not going to go
through all the details,

00:18:01.820 --> 00:18:04.610
but basically you see how
all of the different pieces

00:18:04.610 --> 00:18:06.640
of modern physics get involved.

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:09.100
There's quantum mechanics,
space time, gravity,

00:18:09.100 --> 00:18:12.020
this is Einstein's general
relativity right there,

00:18:12.020 --> 00:18:13.900
all the other forces,
electromagnetism

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:16.300
and the nuclear forces,
the matter particles

00:18:16.300 --> 00:18:19.644
of which we are made, and
the Higgs in the background.

00:18:19.644 --> 00:18:21.310
If you want know more
about the details,

00:18:21.310 --> 00:18:24.440
I did manage to squeeze
it into the book.

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:27.120
But I was told it should
be put into an appendix,

00:18:27.120 --> 00:18:30.130
and the font size is very
small in the appendix.

00:18:30.130 --> 00:18:34.430
But nevertheless, every term
here is explained, briefly.

00:18:34.430 --> 00:18:36.430
It takes a year long
quantum field theory course

00:18:36.430 --> 00:18:38.013
in graduate school
to get the details,

00:18:38.013 --> 00:18:39.680
but at least say what
every term means,

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:42.210
including the i for
example and including

00:18:42.210 --> 00:18:43.950
the k less than lambda.

00:18:43.950 --> 00:18:48.920
What you don't see are causes,
purposes, or reasons why.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:52.230
It's just Laplacian calculation
over and over again.

00:18:52.230 --> 00:18:54.170
This is the modern
version of what

00:18:54.170 --> 00:18:56.770
you need to program
into Laplace's demon

00:18:56.770 --> 00:18:59.050
so that starting from the
position and configuration

00:18:59.050 --> 00:19:01.508
of the world at one point, it
can find out what will happen

00:19:01.508 --> 00:19:04.180
next or what happened before.

00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:06.410
The final criterion
you need for this

00:19:06.410 --> 00:19:08.230
to be a good, successful
theory is that it

00:19:08.230 --> 00:19:09.380
should fit on a T-shirt.

00:19:09.380 --> 00:19:10.610
So we did the experiment.

00:19:10.610 --> 00:19:11.640
There it is.

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:13.330
It totally fits on the T-shirt.

00:19:13.330 --> 00:19:15.655
You can buy them on my website.

00:19:15.655 --> 00:19:19.290
I don't make any money off them,
but you can buy the T-shirt.

00:19:19.290 --> 00:19:23.580
So I want to do at least
one minute of justification

00:19:23.580 --> 00:19:24.890
for this grandiose claim.

00:19:24.890 --> 00:19:25.860
I mean, it's one thing
to have a theory.

00:19:25.860 --> 00:19:27.167
We have lots of theories.

00:19:27.167 --> 00:19:28.500
Our theories are never complete.

00:19:28.500 --> 00:19:31.760
Our theories are never things
we should have 100% credence in.

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:33.490
We should always,
as scientists, be

00:19:33.490 --> 00:19:35.240
willing to improve
upon our theories.

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:37.266
So what gives me the
right to say that

00:19:37.266 --> 00:19:38.890
a million years from
now, this is still

00:19:38.890 --> 00:19:40.990
going to be the
theory underlying

00:19:40.990 --> 00:19:43.690
the particles and forces of
which you and I are made.

00:19:43.690 --> 00:19:45.350
The answer is something
called crossing

00:19:45.350 --> 00:19:48.550
symmetry, which is a feature
of quantum field theory.

00:19:48.550 --> 00:19:50.100
I mention fields.

00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:52.190
Fields are in fact what
you and I are made out of.

00:19:52.190 --> 00:19:54.398
You might have taken a
physics course and been asked,

00:19:54.398 --> 00:19:57.290
is light a particle or a wave,
or is an electron a particle

00:19:57.290 --> 00:19:58.690
or a wave?

00:19:58.690 --> 00:20:00.440
Probably you were
not told the answer.

00:20:00.440 --> 00:20:01.410
It's a wave.

00:20:01.410 --> 00:20:02.910
That's what it is.

00:20:02.910 --> 00:20:05.690
According to quantum mechanics,
the world is made of waves.

00:20:05.690 --> 00:20:09.170
The world looks like particles
when we look closely enough.

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:11.140
But really the way that
we talk about the world

00:20:11.140 --> 00:20:13.735
in modern physics is through
quantum field theory.

00:20:13.735 --> 00:20:15.860
And quantum field theory
uses these little pictures

00:20:15.860 --> 00:20:17.340
called Feynman diagrams.

00:20:17.340 --> 00:20:20.730
My personal claim to fame
in the world of physics

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:23.280
is that the desk I have
in my office at Caltech

00:20:23.280 --> 00:20:25.470
used to be owned
by Richard Feynman.

00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:26.914
So I sit at Feynman's old desk.

00:20:26.914 --> 00:20:29.580
I leave blank pieces of paper in
there hoping some diagrams will

00:20:29.580 --> 00:20:31.740
appear, but it never happens.

00:20:31.740 --> 00:20:34.430
So what Feynman did is to
invent a way of talking about

00:20:34.430 --> 00:20:37.300
what happens in particle physics
and quantum field theory,

00:20:37.300 --> 00:20:40.020
and also how likely
it is to happen.

00:20:40.020 --> 00:20:43.210
So if we have a particle we
know about, like a proton,

00:20:43.210 --> 00:20:44.885
and we imagine there's
a new particle.

00:20:44.885 --> 00:20:46.260
Maybe there's a
new particle that

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:49.980
really does affect how
you choose your food

00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:53.750
or how plants photosynthesize
or how you think,

00:20:53.750 --> 00:20:55.790
well then there must be
a Feynman diagram that

00:20:55.790 --> 00:20:57.620
says that that
particle can interact

00:20:57.620 --> 00:21:00.590
with a proton via
some new interaction.

00:21:00.590 --> 00:21:03.670
And Feynman's rules say how
you can use this diagram

00:21:03.670 --> 00:21:06.800
to calculate how likely
that is to happen,

00:21:06.800 --> 00:21:09.970
the amplitude or the
probability of that process.

00:21:09.970 --> 00:21:11.510
And then crossing
symmetry says--

00:21:11.510 --> 00:21:14.510
this is a diagram that time
evolves from left to right.

00:21:14.510 --> 00:21:16.010
So X comes in, P comes in.

00:21:16.010 --> 00:21:17.970
They just scatter
off of each other.

00:21:17.970 --> 00:21:20.850
Crossing symmetry says that
if this diagram exists,

00:21:20.850 --> 00:21:23.510
I can rotate it
clockwise by 90 degrees

00:21:23.510 --> 00:21:25.912
and get another
diagram that exists.

00:21:25.912 --> 00:21:28.120
So I'm glossing over the
difference between particles

00:21:28.120 --> 00:21:29.250
and antiparticles here.

00:21:29.250 --> 00:21:31.980
Really if this is a proton,
this is still a proton.

00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:35.380
This diagram talks about a
proton and an antiproton coming

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:38.450
together to produce
an X particle

00:21:38.450 --> 00:21:40.890
and an anti-X particle.

00:21:40.890 --> 00:21:42.530
And what crossing
symmetry says is

00:21:42.530 --> 00:21:44.530
if you know how big
this diagram is,

00:21:44.530 --> 00:21:46.402
if you know how likely
that process is,

00:21:46.402 --> 00:21:49.950
you know how likely
this process is.

00:21:49.950 --> 00:21:52.910
So if this new X particle
interacts with protons

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:55.360
or with neutrons or
quarks or neutrinos

00:21:55.360 --> 00:22:00.190
or whatever, strongly enough
to affect your everyday life,

00:22:00.190 --> 00:22:03.820
then we could make it by
smashing together the particles

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:05.600
out of which we are created.

00:22:05.600 --> 00:22:07.400
And the punchline
is we have looked.

00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:09.670
We have smashed together
all the particles.

00:22:09.670 --> 00:22:11.640
We've smashed together
protons and protons.

00:22:11.640 --> 00:22:13.325
That's what the LHC is doing.

00:22:13.325 --> 00:22:15.840
We've done protons and
antiprotons, electrons

00:22:15.840 --> 00:22:19.090
and electrons, electrons and
positrons on down the line.

00:22:19.090 --> 00:22:21.600
We would have loved to find
a new particle like this,

00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:22.990
and we have not done so yet.

00:22:22.990 --> 00:22:25.100
There are no
particles like this.

00:22:25.100 --> 00:22:27.210
The closest we have
is a tiny little bit

00:22:27.210 --> 00:22:29.750
of a hint at the
Large Hadron Collider,

00:22:29.750 --> 00:22:32.830
as of May, 2016,
that there might

00:22:32.830 --> 00:22:35.877
be a new particle that is 800
times the mass of the proton.

00:22:35.877 --> 00:22:36.960
It may or may not be true.

00:22:36.960 --> 00:22:38.060
There's a little bump.

00:22:38.060 --> 00:22:38.850
Maybe it's there.

00:22:38.850 --> 00:22:40.120
We're still looking.

00:22:40.120 --> 00:22:42.340
But even if it is, it
decays away in less than a

00:22:42.340 --> 00:22:42.950
zeptosecond.

00:22:42.950 --> 00:22:46.770
It is not something that affects
your everyday life in any way.

00:22:46.770 --> 00:22:49.680
So in terms of the particles
that actually matter to you

00:22:49.680 --> 00:22:54.890
and me that make us up, we
know the complete collection.

00:22:54.890 --> 00:22:57.360
So the question is, the
big question ahead of us

00:22:57.360 --> 00:23:01.690
today is, if that's true,
why does the manifest world

00:23:01.690 --> 00:23:05.190
of our everyday experience
seem so different

00:23:05.190 --> 00:23:08.190
than the underlying laws of
quantum mechanics and quantum

00:23:08.190 --> 00:23:10.190
field theory and
particle physics?

00:23:10.190 --> 00:23:13.470
And the answer is this
tricky idea called emergence.

00:23:13.470 --> 00:23:15.690
You can have an
underlying layer of

00:23:15.690 --> 00:23:18.740
microscopic fundamental physics
made of particles, forces,

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:20.450
and differential Equations.

00:23:20.450 --> 00:23:22.090
It can do what Laplace said.

00:23:22.090 --> 00:23:25.960
Information is conserved from
moment to moment over time.

00:23:25.960 --> 00:23:28.240
The rules of physics are
patterns written down

00:23:28.240 --> 00:23:30.160
in differential equations.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:32.700
And yet, when you
collect together

00:23:32.700 --> 00:23:37.030
many of these particles, there
can be collective behavior

00:23:37.030 --> 00:23:39.860
that is implicit but
not at all obvious,

00:23:39.860 --> 00:23:41.700
in this microscopic rules.

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:45.620
This collective behavior could
emerge into wholly new concepts

00:23:45.620 --> 00:23:47.650
and vocabularies.

00:23:47.650 --> 00:23:49.980
So the idea that there are
tables and chairs and people

00:23:49.980 --> 00:23:52.950
and planets, that's
nowhere obvious

00:23:52.950 --> 00:23:54.680
in this underlying description.

00:23:54.680 --> 00:23:58.570
But the two levels can be
compatible with each other.

00:23:58.570 --> 00:24:01.530
This is the world of cause
and effect, reasons why,

00:24:01.530 --> 00:24:04.920
dissipation, and most
importantly the arrow of time,

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:07.470
the difference between
past and future.

00:24:07.470 --> 00:24:11.290
So our task today is to see
how this one level can be

00:24:11.290 --> 00:24:13.110
compatible with the other one.

00:24:13.110 --> 00:24:17.640
Why can we think that there are
reasons why causes and effects,

00:24:17.640 --> 00:24:19.180
and for that matter
right and wrong

00:24:19.180 --> 00:24:21.240
and truth and
beauty in the world,

00:24:21.240 --> 00:24:23.740
even though at some
level, deep down, it's

00:24:23.740 --> 00:24:25.790
just stuff happening
according to that equation

00:24:25.790 --> 00:24:27.750
that I showed you.

00:24:27.750 --> 00:24:30.730
So the arrow of time, one
of my favorite topics,

00:24:30.730 --> 00:24:33.910
is simply the fact that
the past and future

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:35.840
are different from each other.

00:24:35.840 --> 00:24:38.930
This is not a surprising
fact if you're Aristotle.

00:24:38.930 --> 00:24:41.250
Motion through time, the
evolution of the universe

00:24:41.250 --> 00:24:42.849
is obviously something profound.

00:24:42.849 --> 00:24:44.390
The past is different
from the future

00:24:44.390 --> 00:24:46.680
because the past
already happened.

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:49.730
But according to Laplace
or to modern physics,

00:24:49.730 --> 00:24:52.470
there's no difference between
moving toward the past

00:24:52.470 --> 00:24:55.030
and moving toward the future
at the microscopic level.

00:24:55.030 --> 00:24:57.220
Only macroscopically
is there a difference,

00:24:57.220 --> 00:24:59.130
and there are many differences.

00:24:59.130 --> 00:25:02.380
You can remember the past, but
you can't remember the future.

00:25:02.380 --> 00:25:04.870
We were all younger in
the past and will be older

00:25:04.870 --> 00:25:05.760
in the future.

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:08.380
Sorry to break that to you.

00:25:08.380 --> 00:25:10.570
Most importantly or
most fundamentally,

00:25:10.570 --> 00:25:12.900
entropy increases over time.

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:14.650
Entropy is the way
that we have of talking

00:25:14.650 --> 00:25:17.440
about the disorderliness,
the randomness,

00:25:17.440 --> 00:25:20.510
the disorganization
of stuff over time.

00:25:20.510 --> 00:25:22.900
And there's a general
principle that organized things

00:25:22.900 --> 00:25:26.580
like unbroken eggs can easily
evolve into disorganized things

00:25:26.580 --> 00:25:29.660
like broken eggs, but never
backward the other way,

00:25:29.660 --> 00:25:31.790
or at least very, very
rarely, or at least

00:25:31.790 --> 00:25:34.040
you need to do a lot of
work to make it happen.

00:25:34.040 --> 00:25:38.380
If you live in a room or you
have an office and it's clean,

00:25:38.380 --> 00:25:41.780
it will naturally happen that
it becomes messy over time.

00:25:41.780 --> 00:25:44.370
If your office or room
is messy, it will never

00:25:44.370 --> 00:25:46.710
clean itself up all by itself.

00:25:46.710 --> 00:25:48.480
You need to do work.

00:25:48.480 --> 00:25:50.497
That's because
entropy is increasing.

00:25:50.497 --> 00:25:53.080
If you'd like to think of it as
the working out of a great law

00:25:53.080 --> 00:25:55.640
of physics, be my guest.

00:25:55.640 --> 00:25:57.320
And the reason why
this is true is

00:25:57.320 --> 00:25:59.960
because there are more
ways to be high entropy

00:25:59.960 --> 00:26:00.960
than to be low entropy.

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:02.570
There are more
arrangements of stuff

00:26:02.570 --> 00:26:04.730
that are messy
than are organized.

00:26:04.730 --> 00:26:07.190
This was the brilliant
insight of Ludwig Boltzmann,

00:26:07.190 --> 00:26:09.500
the 19th century physicist.

00:26:09.500 --> 00:26:14.830
And so therefore if you start in
a configuration of low entropy,

00:26:14.830 --> 00:26:17.830
entropy naturally increases.

00:26:17.830 --> 00:26:21.260
The problem was,
therefore, why isn't

00:26:21.260 --> 00:26:23.520
entropy at its maximum value?

00:26:23.520 --> 00:26:25.270
There are many, many
more ways for entropy

00:26:25.270 --> 00:26:27.340
to be high than for
entropy to be low.

00:26:27.340 --> 00:26:30.510
Why is it true that
entropy was ever low?

00:26:30.510 --> 00:26:32.770
So Boltzmann, in
other words, explains

00:26:32.770 --> 00:26:34.730
why, given the entropy
of the universe today,

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:35.937
it will be higher tomorrow.

00:26:35.937 --> 00:26:38.520
There are more ways to be high
entropy than to be low entropy.

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:42.280
But he does not explain
why it was lower yesterday.

00:26:42.280 --> 00:26:44.057
I'm here to tell you the answer.

00:26:44.057 --> 00:26:45.640
The reason the entropy
of the universe

00:26:45.640 --> 00:26:48.840
was lower yesterday than today
is because it was even lower

00:26:48.840 --> 00:26:51.890
the day before yesterday.

00:26:51.890 --> 00:26:53.425
And the reason why
that's true too

00:26:53.425 --> 00:26:56.330
is because it was even
lower the day before that.

00:26:56.330 --> 00:26:59.710
And this reasoning goes
back 13.7 billion years

00:26:59.710 --> 00:27:01.240
to the Big Bang.

00:27:01.240 --> 00:27:04.505
The reason why the universe
has had a low entropy all along

00:27:04.505 --> 00:27:06.780
is because it started that way.

00:27:06.780 --> 00:27:08.000
Nobody knows why.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:11.520
This is a profound question
for modern cosmology.

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:14.660
But once you give me that, I
can explain all the differences

00:27:14.660 --> 00:27:16.290
between the past and the future.

00:27:16.290 --> 00:27:18.660
So one way of thinking
about it is, we all agree

00:27:18.660 --> 00:27:21.450
that there's no arrow of space.

00:27:21.450 --> 00:27:23.190
If you're out there
in a space suit,

00:27:23.190 --> 00:27:24.680
there would be no difference
between up and down,

00:27:24.680 --> 00:27:26.120
left, right, forward, backward.

00:27:26.120 --> 00:27:27.574
But here in this room there is.

00:27:27.574 --> 00:27:29.990
If I drop the laser pointer,
I know it's going to go down.

00:27:29.990 --> 00:27:32.500
There's an arrow of
space pointing down.

00:27:32.500 --> 00:27:37.050
Nobody thinks that this is
some profound consequence

00:27:37.050 --> 00:27:38.980
of the fundamental
laws of physics.

00:27:38.980 --> 00:27:42.030
It's because we live in the
vicinity of a very influential

00:27:42.030 --> 00:27:44.750
object, namely the Earth.

00:27:44.750 --> 00:27:47.940
The point of this discussion
is that time is like that.

00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:51.230
There is no intrinsic arrow of
time in the laws of physics,

00:27:51.230 --> 00:27:53.710
but we think that there is
in our observable universe

00:27:53.710 --> 00:27:57.180
because we live in the aftermath
of a very influential event,

00:27:57.180 --> 00:27:58.539
the Big Bang.

00:27:58.539 --> 00:28:00.580
I'm not going to explain
why the Big Bang was low

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:01.900
entropy, because nobody knows.

00:28:01.900 --> 00:28:03.720
Don't believe anyone who
comes in here and tells you

00:28:03.720 --> 00:28:04.220
they know.

00:28:04.220 --> 00:28:06.730
It's a good topic
for conversation.

00:28:06.730 --> 00:28:10.590
But given that, we can try
to explain other features

00:28:10.590 --> 00:28:11.770
of the arrow of time.

00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:15.600
For existence, the existence
of memories and causes, right?

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:18.400
Memories are something
where we know something now.

00:28:18.400 --> 00:28:20.830
It implies something
about the past.

00:28:20.830 --> 00:28:22.830
The cause is something
that we do something now,

00:28:22.830 --> 00:28:25.140
it implies something will
happen in the future.

00:28:25.140 --> 00:28:27.590
Where does this
asymmetry come from?

00:28:27.590 --> 00:28:28.650
So here's a memory.

00:28:28.650 --> 00:28:30.770
Here's a picture of
a record of an event.

00:28:30.770 --> 00:28:32.430
This is an egg that was broken.

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:33.888
You're walking down
the street, you

00:28:33.888 --> 00:28:35.950
see a broken egg
on the sidewalk.

00:28:35.950 --> 00:28:38.600
Ask yourself, what does the
future hold for this egg?

00:28:38.600 --> 00:28:40.475
I don't know why you're
asking yourself this.

00:28:40.475 --> 00:28:41.720
You're in a reflective mood.

00:28:41.720 --> 00:28:44.396
What is the future of this
poor egg going to hold?

00:28:44.396 --> 00:28:45.020
You don't know.

00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:46.420
I mean, there's many
different possibilities.

00:28:46.420 --> 00:28:48.080
It could just sit
there for a long time.

00:28:48.080 --> 00:28:49.496
It could wash away
in a rainstorm.

00:28:49.496 --> 00:28:52.010
Someone could clean it up.

00:28:52.010 --> 00:28:55.290
But if you ask yourself what
does the past of the egg

00:28:55.290 --> 00:28:59.010
probably experience, what
are things like for the egg

00:28:59.010 --> 00:29:01.610
recently, with
overwhelming probability

00:29:01.610 --> 00:29:05.830
that egg used to be unbroken,
and someone dropped it.

00:29:05.830 --> 00:29:08.670
Why is it that this
single record-- this

00:29:08.670 --> 00:29:09.960
isn't even moving, right?

00:29:09.960 --> 00:29:12.900
The macroscopic information
is not changing in time.

00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:15.340
The egg is just sitting
there stationary.

00:29:15.340 --> 00:29:18.270
Why are you able to draw
such different conclusions

00:29:18.270 --> 00:29:20.464
about its past than its future?

00:29:20.464 --> 00:29:21.880
The answer is
because secretly you

00:29:21.880 --> 00:29:24.280
know that the Big Bang
had a low entropy.

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:27.410
You don't use that in your
everyday life, but that's why.

00:29:27.410 --> 00:29:30.590
If all you knew is physics and
the macroscopic information

00:29:30.590 --> 00:29:32.049
about the egg, the
number of things

00:29:32.049 --> 00:29:33.589
that could happen
in the future would

00:29:33.589 --> 00:29:35.310
be exactly equal to
the number of things

00:29:35.310 --> 00:29:36.790
that happened in the past.

00:29:36.790 --> 00:29:39.260
But the extra thing you
know is that the universe

00:29:39.260 --> 00:29:40.400
started with low entropy.

00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:43.480
That ties the possible
histories in the past.

00:29:43.480 --> 00:29:46.170
And what that means is
that you know something

00:29:46.170 --> 00:29:49.670
about the past
condition of the egg.

00:29:49.670 --> 00:29:51.289
Unbroken eggs lead
to broken eggs,

00:29:51.289 --> 00:29:52.830
because that's the
easiest way to get

00:29:52.830 --> 00:29:56.510
to broken eggs given the low
entropy past of the universe.

00:29:56.510 --> 00:29:58.930
And causes and effects
work the same way.

00:29:58.930 --> 00:30:00.597
Just like an egg is
something-- a memory

00:30:00.597 --> 00:30:02.930
is something that if it were
a little bit different now,

00:30:02.930 --> 00:30:05.060
it would imply something
different about the past.

00:30:05.060 --> 00:30:06.310
Think about what a cause does.

00:30:06.310 --> 00:30:10.039
If I say I move my hand
and the book moves,

00:30:10.039 --> 00:30:11.830
if I move my hand a
little bit differently,

00:30:11.830 --> 00:30:15.390
like I missed the book, then
it wouldn't have moved, right?

00:30:15.390 --> 00:30:21.600
So if my hand moving is the
cause of the book moving,

00:30:21.600 --> 00:30:24.230
that's because if my hand had
done something very different,

00:30:24.230 --> 00:30:26.396
it would have implied
something different about what

00:30:26.396 --> 00:30:27.125
comes next.

00:30:27.125 --> 00:30:29.337
If I'm waving my
hand over here, I

00:30:29.337 --> 00:30:30.920
could wave in a
slightly different way

00:30:30.920 --> 00:30:32.770
and it doesn't imply anything
different about the book.

00:30:32.770 --> 00:30:35.480
And therefore this hand moving
is not the cause of the book.

00:30:35.480 --> 00:30:37.521
It's the thing that came
right next to it that is

00:30:37.521 --> 00:30:39.040
the cause of the book moving.

00:30:39.040 --> 00:30:41.000
The idea that causes
proceed effects

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:46.540
emerges in our macroscopic world
because of the arrow of time.

00:30:46.540 --> 00:30:49.270
So that is the first
little baby step

00:30:49.270 --> 00:30:51.710
towards reconciling
our everyday world

00:30:51.710 --> 00:30:55.250
with this impersonal,
calculational underlying

00:30:55.250 --> 00:30:56.530
laws of physics.

00:30:56.530 --> 00:30:59.010
The next step is if
the universe is just

00:30:59.010 --> 00:31:01.330
a story of stuff
becoming more and more

00:31:01.330 --> 00:31:06.390
