So it's today when gravity
has pulled things together,

00:34:06.020 --> 00:34:08.889
made the universal lumpy,
brought into existence planets

00:34:08.889 --> 00:34:12.810
and stars and galaxies,
biospheres and people

00:34:12.810 --> 00:34:15.850
that the universe is
interesting and complex.

00:34:15.850 --> 00:34:18.469
As small as we are compared
to the vastness of the cosmos,

00:34:18.469 --> 00:34:22.100
we live in the interesting part
of the history of the universe

00:34:22.100 --> 00:34:24.170
for exactly that reason.

00:34:24.170 --> 00:34:25.840
And this kind of
reasoning can help

00:34:25.840 --> 00:34:30.330
us explain even questions
like why life itself exists.

00:34:30.330 --> 00:34:34.050
So I like to tell the story,
I was once on a plane flight

00:34:34.050 --> 00:34:36.340
going to a conference
to give a talk.

00:34:36.340 --> 00:34:40.800
And as often happens, if you're
a physicist or a cosmologist,

00:34:40.800 --> 00:34:42.770
people find that
out and they want

00:34:42.770 --> 00:34:44.790
to tell you their theories.

00:34:44.790 --> 00:34:47.199
Everyone it seems has a
theory about the universe.

00:34:47.199 --> 00:34:50.389
I was reading some papers
about statistical mechanics

00:34:50.389 --> 00:34:52.110
and the origin of life.

00:34:52.110 --> 00:34:53.860
The guy sitting next
to me on the airplane

00:34:53.860 --> 00:34:55.974
says, oh yes, I've
read those papers.

00:34:55.974 --> 00:34:59.570
So I'm a little bit skeptical.

00:34:59.570 --> 00:35:02.640
But he says in fact I can
tell you the purpose of life.

00:35:02.640 --> 00:35:04.560
And I'm very skeptical.

00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:07.250
But he says the purpose of
life is to hydrogenation

00:35:07.250 --> 00:35:08.695
carbon dioxide.

00:35:08.695 --> 00:35:12.740
This is not the response
I was expecting to get.

00:35:12.740 --> 00:35:15.760
It turns out that I was seated
next to Dr Michael Russell, one

00:35:15.760 --> 00:35:17.740
of the world's experts
in abiogenesis,

00:35:17.740 --> 00:35:18.870
the origin of life.

00:35:18.870 --> 00:35:23.950
He works at JPL, just down
the street from Caltech.

00:35:23.950 --> 00:35:25.865
And he writes papers
with graphs like this.

00:35:25.865 --> 00:35:29.950
And he was very serious about
the hydrogenation business.

00:35:29.950 --> 00:35:32.610
What he means-- and again, we
don't know whether this is true

00:35:32.610 --> 00:35:33.110
or not.

00:35:33.110 --> 00:35:34.200
We don't know how life begins.

00:35:34.200 --> 00:35:36.241
This is one of the theories
people are advancing.

00:35:36.241 --> 00:35:38.560
But you can see in
all these theories,

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:40.860
you can sort of see
the hints of how

00:35:40.860 --> 00:35:42.780
a really, really
difficult problem suddenly

00:35:42.780 --> 00:35:45.141
seems to be a lot more soluble.

00:35:45.141 --> 00:35:46.890
So what Russell's
pointing out, that there

00:35:46.890 --> 00:35:48.950
are many environments
in the early Earth

00:35:48.950 --> 00:35:52.880
where there's a lot of carbon
dioxide and a lot of hydrogen.

00:35:52.880 --> 00:35:55.500
And that is a low
entropy configuration.

00:35:55.500 --> 00:35:57.620
And that's what we
call high free energy.

00:35:57.620 --> 00:36:01.620
So this is free energy versus
different compound structures.

00:36:01.620 --> 00:36:04.340
If you took that carbon,
removed the oxygen,

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:07.390
and palled them all up with
a bunch of hydrogen atoms,

00:36:07.390 --> 00:36:08.900
the carbon would
now be in methane,

00:36:08.900 --> 00:36:11.480
and the entropy
would be much higher.

00:36:11.480 --> 00:36:13.900
In some sense,
the carbon dioxide

00:36:13.900 --> 00:36:15.660
wants to become methane.

00:36:15.660 --> 00:36:18.810
The problem is that
there's a barrier,

00:36:18.810 --> 00:36:21.930
that all the ways to
get from CO2 to CH4

00:36:21.930 --> 00:36:26.010
involve going through even
lower entropy configurations--

00:36:26.010 --> 00:36:28.430
higher free energy
configurations.

00:36:28.430 --> 00:36:30.290
And that can't
happen all by itself.

00:36:30.290 --> 00:36:32.507
It's not like lighting
a match on a candle.

00:36:32.507 --> 00:36:34.090
But what Russell
points out is that it

00:36:34.090 --> 00:36:38.320
can happen if there's a
complicated network of chemical

00:36:38.320 --> 00:36:41.190
reactions brought together
in just the right way

00:36:41.190 --> 00:36:43.800
with the right
catalysts and so forth.

00:36:43.800 --> 00:36:46.270
And that kind of network
in the right conditions

00:36:46.270 --> 00:36:50.760
could be the precursor of the
metabolism of modern life.

00:36:50.760 --> 00:36:54.110
So in the 1980s on the basis
of this kind of reasoning,

00:36:54.110 --> 00:36:57.100
Russell predicted the
existence of a certain kind

00:36:57.100 --> 00:37:00.440
of underwater geological
formation, what

00:37:00.440 --> 00:37:04.430
we call warm alkaline
hydrothermal vents.

00:37:04.430 --> 00:37:07.040
And after he made the
prediction, they found one.

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:12.970
This is the lost city
configuration, lost city--

00:37:12.970 --> 00:37:13.970
I don't know what it is.

00:37:13.970 --> 00:37:19.350
It's a bunch of stuff happening
under the mid-Atlantic Ocean.

00:37:19.350 --> 00:37:20.890
And it has exactly
the properties

00:37:20.890 --> 00:37:24.229
that you would need to get
this kind of reaction starting.

00:37:24.229 --> 00:37:26.270
There might be many of
them underneath the ocean.

00:37:26.270 --> 00:37:28.144
This is something that
we think will probably

00:37:28.144 --> 00:37:31.280
last there for tens of thousands
of years before it washes away.

00:37:31.280 --> 00:37:33.300
And you make new ones.

00:37:33.300 --> 00:37:36.520
So we don't know how life began.

00:37:36.520 --> 00:37:37.980
But this way of
thinking about it

00:37:37.980 --> 00:37:41.510
is interesting because rather
than looking at it as life

00:37:41.510 --> 00:37:45.080
exists, how did it possibly
start, this point of view

00:37:45.080 --> 00:37:47.440
is saying we have a
puzzle, how to increase

00:37:47.440 --> 00:37:49.180
the entropy of the
early Earth, and life

00:37:49.180 --> 00:37:51.249
is the solution to that puzzle.

00:37:51.249 --> 00:37:52.790
Of course you need
to get it together

00:37:52.790 --> 00:37:56.180
with other things like cell
walls and replication and RNA

00:37:56.180 --> 00:37:56.947
and so forth.

00:37:56.947 --> 00:37:58.530
Putting all those
pieces of the puzzle

00:37:58.530 --> 00:38:01.750
together is full employment
for abiogenesis researchers

00:38:01.750 --> 00:38:04.410
for the next hundred
years probably.

00:38:04.410 --> 00:38:07.210
But then once that gets
started, once you have life,

00:38:07.210 --> 00:38:08.510
then things get interesting.

00:38:08.510 --> 00:38:10.770
What is life anyway?

00:38:10.770 --> 00:38:12.600
Nobody knows that either.

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:14.940
I like the definition given
by the physicist Erwin

00:38:14.940 --> 00:38:15.766
Schrodinger.

00:38:15.766 --> 00:38:17.390
Schrodinger said that
life is something

00:38:17.390 --> 00:38:20.950
that keeps moving long
after it should've stopped.

00:38:20.950 --> 00:38:22.455
What does he mean by that?

00:38:22.455 --> 00:38:25.512
He means if you put a dead
thing in a bowl of water,

00:38:25.512 --> 00:38:26.470
it will just sit there.

00:38:26.470 --> 00:38:27.345
It won't do anything.

00:38:27.345 --> 00:38:30.647
If you put a living thing like
a goldfish, in my experience

00:38:30.647 --> 00:38:32.480
it will also just die
and then it will float

00:38:32.480 --> 00:38:35.050
to the bottom of the thing.

00:38:35.050 --> 00:38:37.810
But if you give it
food, the living thing

00:38:37.810 --> 00:38:39.280
can last for a long time.

00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:40.600
What is food?

00:38:40.600 --> 00:38:44.300
Food is energy in
a low entropy form.

00:38:44.300 --> 00:38:46.917
That's exactly what
we get from the sun.

00:38:46.917 --> 00:38:48.500
The sun gives us
energy, and you might

00:38:48.500 --> 00:38:49.750
think that's what's important.

00:38:49.750 --> 00:38:51.180
The sun gives us energy.

00:38:51.180 --> 00:38:53.570
But if the whole sky were
the temperature of the sun,

00:38:53.570 --> 00:38:55.319
none of us would be
here talking about it.

00:38:55.319 --> 00:38:57.360
You would come to
thermal equilibrium.

00:38:57.360 --> 00:39:00.800
What the sun gives us
is low entropy energy.

00:39:00.800 --> 00:39:03.630
For every one photon of
light we get from the sun,

00:39:03.630 --> 00:39:06.970
we give back 20 photons
back to the universe.

00:39:06.970 --> 00:39:08.120
But we get visible light.

00:39:08.120 --> 00:39:10.200
We radiate infrared.

00:39:10.200 --> 00:39:14.190
We radiate photons with
1/20 of the energy each.

00:39:14.190 --> 00:39:16.830
So we get back the same
energy we get, but only

00:39:16.830 --> 00:39:20.430
after increasing its
entropy by a factor of 20,

00:39:20.430 --> 00:39:22.650
by photosynthesizing,
chewing our cud,

00:39:22.650 --> 00:39:24.947
having meetings, writing
software, et cetera.

00:39:24.947 --> 00:39:26.530
Then we radiate back
into the universe

00:39:26.530 --> 00:39:30.770
having increased its disorder
by a considerable fraction.

00:39:30.770 --> 00:39:34.325
And that explains how an
individual organism can persist

00:39:34.325 --> 00:39:36.244
and survive and sustain itself.

00:39:36.244 --> 00:39:37.910
But of course the
great thing about life

00:39:37.910 --> 00:39:41.530
is that it reproduces
and there are mutations.

00:39:41.530 --> 00:39:44.600
And therefore evolution
gets off the ground.

00:39:44.600 --> 00:39:47.170
So if our goal is
to understand how

00:39:47.170 --> 00:39:51.720
ideas like cause and effect
and even purposes can arise,

00:39:51.720 --> 00:39:53.470
evolution is a
wonderful mechanism

00:39:53.470 --> 00:39:55.420
for making that happen.

00:39:55.420 --> 00:39:57.540
Why do giraffes have long necks?

00:39:57.540 --> 00:40:00.680
Well one answer is because
of the state of the universe

00:40:00.680 --> 00:40:02.230
and the laws of physics.

00:40:02.230 --> 00:40:04.890
That's not a very
helpful answer, is it?

00:40:04.890 --> 00:40:08.830
Another answer is to reach these
leaves up there in the tree.

00:40:08.830 --> 00:40:11.820
Evolution can be thought
of as a search strategy

00:40:11.820 --> 00:40:13.590
for this different
genetic information,

00:40:13.590 --> 00:40:16.190
for the genome that
passes down to try

00:40:16.190 --> 00:40:19.020
to maximize the chances
of reproductive success

00:40:19.020 --> 00:40:21.150
in this particular environment.

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:26.570
And given that strategy, it's
perfectly OK to say the reason

00:40:26.570 --> 00:40:30.490
why the giraffe has a long
neck is to reach those leaves.

00:40:30.490 --> 00:40:33.940
You can also see something
like this in simple computer

00:40:33.940 --> 00:40:35.010
examples.

00:40:35.010 --> 00:40:37.970
This is a cellular automaton
invented by computer scientist

00:40:37.970 --> 00:40:39.110
Melanie Mitchell.

00:40:39.110 --> 00:40:40.780
She calls it Robby the Robot.

00:40:40.780 --> 00:40:42.220
Robby had a party last night.

00:40:42.220 --> 00:40:44.590
There are beer cans
scattered all over his house.

00:40:44.590 --> 00:40:47.346
What's the best algorithm
to pick up the beer cans?

00:40:47.346 --> 00:40:48.720
Many of you are
probably familiar

00:40:48.720 --> 00:40:50.510
with genetic algorithms.

00:40:50.510 --> 00:40:53.440
You just pick some random
strategies, let them evolve.

00:40:53.440 --> 00:40:56.100
That is to say, find out which
ones are most successful,

00:40:56.100 --> 00:40:56.960
cull them.

00:40:56.960 --> 00:40:58.170
Randomly mutate them.

00:40:58.170 --> 00:41:00.211
Find out which ones of
those are most successful.

00:41:00.211 --> 00:41:01.130
Repeat this.

00:41:01.130 --> 00:41:03.040
And in a very few
generations, Robbie

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:07.610
finds a better strategy than
its human designers ever found.

00:41:07.610 --> 00:41:09.470
And once it has that
strategy, are you

00:41:09.470 --> 00:41:11.660
allowed to say Robbie
is quote, unquote,

00:41:11.660 --> 00:41:14.810
trying its best to
pick up the cans?

00:41:14.810 --> 00:41:17.180
Sure, that's what
I'm trying to say.

00:41:17.180 --> 00:41:20.710
There's no such thing as
a real true purpose that

00:41:20.710 --> 00:41:23.980
goes above and beyond a
way of talking about what

00:41:23.980 --> 00:41:25.930
happens in the physical world.

00:41:25.930 --> 00:41:28.680
Evolution, laws of physics,
and the arrow of time

00:41:28.680 --> 00:41:31.310
make it perfectly sensible
that such ways of talking

00:41:31.310 --> 00:41:35.550
would become convenient and
useful as complicated organisms

00:41:35.550 --> 00:41:37.490
adapt and go on.

00:41:37.490 --> 00:41:40.150
And that even
counts for thinking,

00:41:40.150 --> 00:41:42.050
for consciousness itself.

00:41:42.050 --> 00:41:45.204
We again do not know how
consciousness arose either.

00:41:45.204 --> 00:41:46.870
We don't even know
what consciousness is

00:41:46.870 --> 00:41:48.190
or how it works.

00:41:48.190 --> 00:41:50.860
But we can see little
steps that might

00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:53.200
have happened along the way.

00:41:53.200 --> 00:41:55.850
So Malcolm MacIver, who's
an engineer at Northwestern,

00:41:55.850 --> 00:41:59.430
likes to talk about the first
fish to flap up onto land.

00:41:59.430 --> 00:42:01.514
The evolutionary
pressures on land

00:42:01.514 --> 00:42:03.680
are very, very different
than those under the water.

00:42:03.680 --> 00:42:06.430
If you're under the water,
you can't see very far.

00:42:06.430 --> 00:42:09.130
The attenuation length of
the photons is a few meters.

00:42:09.130 --> 00:42:11.650
So you're swimming around
at a few meters per second,

00:42:11.650 --> 00:42:15.340
you need to be able to
instantly react to what you see.

00:42:15.340 --> 00:42:17.230
But then you climb up
onto land, and now you

00:42:17.230 --> 00:42:18.950
can see for kilometers.

00:42:18.950 --> 00:42:22.200
So there's a whole new
evolutionary pressure which

00:42:22.200 --> 00:42:24.290
is to make a smart decision.

00:42:24.290 --> 00:42:27.335
You had the time to
think about what to do.

00:42:27.335 --> 00:42:30.970
And what that means is that
developing the capacity

00:42:30.970 --> 00:42:34.560
to contemplate different
hypothetical futures

00:42:34.560 --> 00:42:36.630
becomes a smart thing to do.

00:42:36.630 --> 00:42:37.540
And we can look back.

00:42:37.540 --> 00:42:39.490
We can do the neuroscience
and look in your brain.

00:42:39.490 --> 00:42:41.060
What are you doing when
you're contemplating

00:42:41.060 --> 00:42:42.726
hypothetical futures,
when you're really

00:42:42.726 --> 00:42:45.650
sort of consciously
imagining different things?

00:42:45.650 --> 00:42:48.150
It's not a whole new
module of your brain.

00:42:48.150 --> 00:42:50.310
You're using the same
part of your brain

00:42:50.310 --> 00:42:52.210
that gets used when
you recall a memory.

00:42:52.210 --> 00:42:54.840
This is exactly what
evolution likes to do,

00:42:54.840 --> 00:42:58.590
to repurpose all parts of
the functional organism

00:42:58.590 --> 00:43:00.480
to do new tasks.

00:43:00.480 --> 00:43:04.330
Imagining the future is one
part of being conscious.

00:43:04.330 --> 00:43:06.300
It's not the whole
thing obviously.

00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:08.440
But again you could see
how it would happen.

00:43:08.440 --> 00:43:11.280
We don't need to invoke
anything beyond the particles

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:15.390
and fields of the Core Theory
to explain our consciousness.

00:43:15.390 --> 00:43:17.800
Here is a picture of my head.

00:43:17.800 --> 00:43:19.020
It's not to scale.

00:43:19.020 --> 00:43:21.670
But this was a map
made in the laboratory

00:43:21.670 --> 00:43:23.734
of David Poeppel at NYU.

00:43:23.734 --> 00:43:25.150
It's evidence that
I actually have

00:43:25.150 --> 00:43:28.470
a brain inside my skull,
which I was happy to see.

00:43:28.470 --> 00:43:31.610
When you have a
thought, in your neurons

00:43:31.610 --> 00:43:33.700
there are literally
charged particles jumping

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:35.140
from one neuron to another.

00:43:35.140 --> 00:43:37.930
Any physicists will tell you,
following the Core Theory,

00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:41.990
that charged particles in
motion create magnetic fields.

00:43:41.990 --> 00:43:45.260
So this is an MEG, a
magnetoencephalograph.

00:43:45.260 --> 00:43:48.440
It is literally an image
of the tiny magnetic fields

00:43:48.440 --> 00:43:51.550
that stick outside of my skull
while I was hearing some sounds

00:43:51.550 --> 00:43:53.430
and my neurons were
going ah yes, you

00:43:53.430 --> 00:43:55.700
were hearing some sounds.

00:43:55.700 --> 00:43:57.940
Now this isn't evidence
of anything very strong,

00:43:57.940 --> 00:44:00.890
just a reminder of
the obvious fact

00:44:00.890 --> 00:44:03.210
that your thoughts
and your dreams

00:44:03.210 --> 00:44:05.590
and your aspirations
and your emotions

00:44:05.590 --> 00:44:09.120
are correlated with physical
goings on inside your brain.

00:44:09.120 --> 00:44:11.710
We don't need to go
beyond that to explain

00:44:11.710 --> 00:44:14.150
what is it that is happening
when you are thinking.

00:44:14.150 --> 00:44:15.780
This is again an
ancient argument.

00:44:15.780 --> 00:44:17.620
It goes back to these folks.

00:44:17.620 --> 00:44:21.250
This is Renee Descartes, famous
physicist, famous mathematician

00:44:21.250 --> 00:44:22.350
also.

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:24.470
And this is Princess
Elizabeth of Bohemia,

00:44:24.470 --> 00:44:26.950
considerably less famous.

00:44:26.950 --> 00:44:30.720
But they became friends and they
carried on a long conversation,

00:44:30.720 --> 00:44:32.430
basically because
Descartes was always

00:44:32.430 --> 00:44:34.470
looking for a potential patron.

00:44:34.470 --> 00:44:37.475
And even an exiled royal family
like Princess Elizabeth's was

00:44:37.475 --> 00:44:40.170
is better than no
royal family at all.

00:44:40.170 --> 00:44:42.410
Unfortunately she did
not become his patron,

00:44:42.410 --> 00:44:45.360
and she didn't give him a
hard time about his ideas.

00:44:45.360 --> 00:44:48.970
One of Descartes' favorite
ideas was mind body dualism.

00:44:48.970 --> 00:44:50.530
He felt that the
mind or the soul

00:44:50.530 --> 00:44:53.590
was something immaterial
and separate from the body.

00:44:53.590 --> 00:44:56.920
And Elizabeth pressed
him on how in the world

00:44:56.920 --> 00:44:59.255
could something immaterial
and without any location

00:44:59.255 --> 00:45:04.390
could possibly influence the
physical reality of our body.

00:45:04.390 --> 00:45:05.340
So he had a theory.

00:45:05.340 --> 00:45:07.360
This is the pineal
gland in your brain.

00:45:07.360 --> 00:45:08.860
It's the one part
of your brain that

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:11.380
is not broken into two,
two different hemispheres.

00:45:11.380 --> 00:45:13.715
So Descartes drew this
picture and literally proposed

00:45:13.715 --> 00:45:16.830
that the soul communicated
through your pineal gland

00:45:16.830 --> 00:45:18.200
with your body.

00:45:18.200 --> 00:45:21.080
Nobody ever bought
this explanation.

00:45:21.080 --> 00:45:23.630
But the point is that if
Elizabeth were alive today,

00:45:23.630 --> 00:45:25.970
she would point at the
equation for the Core Theory

00:45:25.970 --> 00:45:27.761
and say if you want to
believe in something

00:45:27.761 --> 00:45:29.670
over and above the
physical world,

00:45:29.670 --> 00:45:32.230
how does that change the
behavior of the particles

00:45:32.230 --> 00:45:36.140
in your brain as it is predicted
by that Core Theory equation?

00:45:36.140 --> 00:45:37.640
It's not enough to
say, well there's

00:45:37.640 --> 00:45:39.270
things we don't understand.

00:45:39.270 --> 00:45:41.220
If you don't think that
the brain is simply

00:45:41.220 --> 00:45:44.800
the workings out of physical
matter at some level,

00:45:44.800 --> 00:45:47.300
then you're saying
that equation is wrong.

00:45:47.300 --> 00:45:49.180
And saying how that
equation is wrong

00:45:49.180 --> 00:45:51.532
is a daunting
obstacle to overcome

00:45:51.532 --> 00:45:52.990
if you think that
the world is more

00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:55.360
than just the physical stuff.

00:45:55.360 --> 00:45:57.015
And you don't need
to think that.

00:45:57.015 --> 00:45:59.140
Even if you think the world
is just physical stuff,

00:45:59.140 --> 00:46:02.084
it's perfectly OK
to talk about things

00:46:02.084 --> 00:46:03.500
that we like to
talk about when we

00:46:03.500 --> 00:46:06.220
discuss human beings like
choice and responsibility

00:46:06.220 --> 00:46:09.060
and morality, for exactly
the same reason it's

00:46:09.060 --> 00:46:12.990
OK to talk about temperature and
density and pressure in a fluid

00:46:12.990 --> 00:46:15.810
even though we know it's
really made of atoms.

00:46:15.810 --> 00:46:19.020
These are emergent
features of the world.

00:46:19.020 --> 00:46:21.660
If you're Laplace's demon,
you can predict the future.

00:46:21.660 --> 00:46:22.780
That is true.

00:46:22.780 --> 00:46:25.550
There's no such thing as
free will in the world

00:46:25.550 --> 00:46:27.150
of Laplace's demon.

00:46:27.150 --> 00:46:28.990
But we're not in that world.

00:46:28.990 --> 00:46:30.290
None of us has that ability.

00:46:30.290 --> 00:46:33.320
None of us knows the
requisite information.

00:46:33.320 --> 00:46:36.450
Therefore, the best
way we have to model

00:46:36.450 --> 00:46:39.570
the behavior of real
human beings, real agents

00:46:39.570 --> 00:46:44.500
in the world, is as creatures
who are able to make decisions.

00:46:44.500 --> 00:46:48.310
The problem only arises when
you mix up the vocabularies.

00:46:48.310 --> 00:46:51.300
There are different vocabularies
that can both be true,

00:46:51.300 --> 00:46:54.367
people making choices and atoms
obeying the laws of physics.

00:46:54.367 --> 00:46:55.950
But you have to pick
one or the other.

00:46:55.950 --> 00:46:57.480
You walk up to your
closet and say,

00:46:57.480 --> 00:47:00.380
am I going to wear the red
shirt or the blue shirt?

00:47:00.380 --> 00:47:02.930
Oh, I'll just do whatever my
atoms say the laws of physics

00:47:02.930 --> 00:47:04.180
are going to tell them to do.

00:47:04.180 --> 00:47:06.449
That does not make sense.

00:47:06.449 --> 00:47:07.990
You can talk about
what your atoms do

00:47:07.990 --> 00:47:09.280
or what you're going to do.

00:47:09.280 --> 00:47:11.630
You can't talk
about both at once.

00:47:11.630 --> 00:47:14.500
So this picture of the
world as just governed

00:47:14.500 --> 00:47:17.210
by the laws of
physics isn't as bad

00:47:17.210 --> 00:47:21.300
as you might think in terms
of recovering the human scale

00:47:21.300 --> 00:47:24.130
world of meaning and
mattering and so forth.

00:47:24.130 --> 00:47:27.962
But there is a downside, namely
that you're going to die.

00:47:27.962 --> 00:47:29.920
If you're made of the
stuff of the Core Theory,

00:47:29.920 --> 00:47:33.510
if you're made out of the atoms
and particles, then when you

00:47:33.510 --> 00:47:36.300
die there's no place
for the information

00:47:36.300 --> 00:47:38.010
that was in your brain to go.

00:47:38.010 --> 00:47:40.100
There's no known
forces or particles

00:47:40.100 --> 00:47:43.030
that could carry that away if
your atoms are actually still

00:47:43.030 --> 00:47:44.640
there in your brain.

00:47:44.640 --> 00:47:46.070
So one way of
driving that home is

00:47:46.070 --> 00:47:48.980
to look at this
plot that was made.

00:47:48.980 --> 00:47:51.290
There's some
complexity theorists

00:47:51.290 --> 00:47:54.590
who like to study
scaling laws in biology.

00:47:54.590 --> 00:47:57.030
It turns out that
for mammals, there's

00:47:57.030 --> 00:48:01.190
a scaling law that relates
your heartbeat to your mass,

00:48:01.190 --> 00:48:05.140
and also your life
expectancy to your mass.

00:48:05.140 --> 00:48:07.270
And they cancel out.

00:48:07.270 --> 00:48:10.020
So everywhere along this
curve, the total number

00:48:10.020 --> 00:48:15.340
of heartbeats in the lifespan
of a mammal is about the same.

00:48:15.340 --> 00:48:18.750
It's about 1.5
billion heartbeats.

00:48:18.750 --> 00:48:20.280
Now humans are the exception.

00:48:20.280 --> 00:48:24.320
Because we invented
medicine, Obamacare, and now

00:48:24.320 --> 00:48:27.460
we live for about
twice as long as you

00:48:27.460 --> 00:48:30.186
would have predicted on the
basis of this scaling relation.

00:48:30.186 --> 00:48:32.060
But then again before
we had modern medicine,

00:48:32.060 --> 00:48:36.440
we lived for 30 or 40
years, right on the line.

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:41.450
So that means that we get
about 3 billion heartbeats

00:48:41.450 --> 00:48:42.610
in our lives.

00:48:42.610 --> 00:48:44.750
There's no law of
physics that says this.

00:48:44.750 --> 00:48:47.780
Biological progress can
certainly extend our lifespan

00:48:47.780 --> 00:48:49.160
way, way longer than this.

00:48:49.160 --> 00:48:51.110
But we're not there yet.

00:48:51.110 --> 00:48:53.485
And if you believe that you
are a bunch of particles that

00:48:53.485 --> 00:48:55.700
are interacting
under that equation,

00:48:55.700 --> 00:48:57.600
this is the span of your life.

00:48:57.600 --> 00:49:00.120
You do not continue
on after that.

00:49:00.120 --> 00:49:02.550
And the 3 billion is
kind of a big number.

00:49:02.550 --> 00:49:04.130
3 billion is pretty
big, but it's not

00:49:04.130 --> 00:49:06.930
limitless by any stretch
of the imagination.

00:49:06.930 --> 00:49:10.360
To me, claims like
well, if I'm just stuff

00:49:10.360 --> 00:49:12.520
obeying the laws of physics
removes all the meaning

00:49:12.520 --> 00:49:15.870
and mattering from my
life don't hold water,

00:49:15.870 --> 00:49:17.390
because to me the
fact that I only

00:49:17.390 --> 00:49:19.240
have this small
period of time makes

00:49:19.240 --> 00:49:21.980
every little bit of that
period much more precious.

00:49:21.980 --> 00:49:25.495
Every one of your heartbeats
should be used to good effect.

00:49:25.495 --> 00:49:26.870
One way I like to
drive this home

00:49:26.870 --> 00:49:32.950
is the last slide is the pale
blue dot image of the Earth.

00:49:32.950 --> 00:49:35.740
So the "Voyager" spacecraft,
one of the first spacecraft that

00:49:35.740 --> 00:49:38.820
left the solar system, when
it was 4 billion miles away,

00:49:38.820 --> 00:49:41.140
Carl Sagan and his
team convinced NASA

00:49:41.140 --> 00:49:42.902
to turn it around
and take a parting

00:49:42.902 --> 00:49:45.360
shot, a photograph of the Earth
and the rest of the planets

00:49:45.360 --> 00:49:46.400
in the solar system.

00:49:46.400 --> 00:49:48.880
So that little dot is us.

00:49:48.880 --> 00:49:51.500
That's the Earth,
the pale blue dot.

00:49:51.500 --> 00:49:54.310
Every human being who has
ever lived is in that picture,

00:49:54.310 --> 00:49:57.199
or at least their atoms
are in that picture.

00:49:57.199 --> 00:49:58.740
So on the one hand,
it makes you feel

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:02.600
very small to think that all of
us are just in that little bit.

00:50:02.600 --> 00:50:05.150
And this is not anywhere
near the whole universe

00:50:05.150 --> 00:50:07.040
that we're looking at right now.

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:09.880
On the other hand, we
did take the picture.

00:50:09.880 --> 00:50:11.940
That's pretty good.

00:50:11.940 --> 00:50:15.150
It's a selfie for
the whole Earth.

00:50:15.150 --> 00:50:16.690
"Voyager's" just
an elaborate selfie

00:50:16.690 --> 00:50:19.600
stick out there letting us
take a picture of ourselves.

00:50:19.600 --> 00:50:22.140
But you know what, the
ability to take a selfie

00:50:22.140 --> 00:50:23.717
shouldn't be underestimated.

00:50:23.717 --> 00:50:25.800
It is a reflection of the
fact that even though we

00:50:25.800 --> 00:50:28.010
are very tiny compared
to the universe,

00:50:28.010 --> 00:50:32.410
both in space and in time,
we are in that complex phase.

00:50:32.410 --> 00:50:35.730
We are part of the universe
that has gained the ability

00:50:35.730 --> 00:50:38.590
to think about ourselves, to
be self aware, to make choices

00:50:38.590 --> 00:50:40.980
for ourselves on the basis
of rational reflection,

00:50:40.980 --> 00:50:43.560
to create technological
marvels that

00:50:43.560 --> 00:50:46.420
can help us look at ourselves
and think about what to do next

00:50:46.420 --> 00:50:48.850
rather than just moving
from moment to moment.

00:50:48.850 --> 00:50:52.050
That's both the world we
live in, which is true,

00:50:52.050 --> 00:50:55.610
and it's a world that we can
try to work towards making

00:50:55.610 --> 00:50:57.920
the best we can, which is good.

00:50:57.920 --> 00:50:58.790
Thank you very much.

00:50:58.790 --> 00:51:01.778
