00:51:06.565 --> 00:51:08.190
AUDIENCE: So you
connected the Big Bang

00:51:08.190 --> 00:51:10.100
to the arrow of
time and the fact

00:51:10.100 --> 00:51:12.400
that the past seems
different from the future.

00:51:12.400 --> 00:51:14.200
Can you also sort
of use it to give

00:51:14.200 --> 00:51:17.794
an explanation for why it seems
impossible to go back in time?

00:51:17.794 --> 00:51:19.085
SEAN CARROLL: Well, yes and no.

00:51:19.085 --> 00:51:20.210
So this is a good question.

00:51:20.210 --> 00:51:21.970
The question is,
there's an arrow of time

00:51:21.970 --> 00:51:24.530
that we attribute to low
entropy of the Big Bang.

00:51:24.530 --> 00:51:27.520
What about going
backward in time?

00:51:27.520 --> 00:51:30.220
Mostly the fact that we
can't go back in time

00:51:30.220 --> 00:51:32.960
is because time is
only one dimensional.

00:51:32.960 --> 00:51:34.120
That's the real reason.

00:51:34.120 --> 00:51:37.355
We can go around in
space because space

00:51:37.355 --> 00:51:38.400
is three dimensional.

00:51:38.400 --> 00:51:40.530
If time were two
dimensional, there'd

00:51:40.530 --> 00:51:43.201
be no trouble to go
back to the past.

00:51:43.201 --> 00:51:45.700
Basically the fact that time
is one dimensional and the fact

00:51:45.700 --> 00:51:48.799
that the world happens once
at every moment in time

00:51:48.799 --> 00:51:50.840
means there's just no way
to get there from here.

00:51:50.840 --> 00:51:53.890
It is actually not
in any direct way

00:51:53.890 --> 00:51:57.121
related to what we
call the arrow of time.

00:51:57.121 --> 00:51:59.190
Now that's complicated
by the fact that

00:51:59.190 --> 00:52:02.100
in Einstein's theory of general
relativity, space and time

00:52:02.100 --> 00:52:02.707
are flexible.

00:52:02.707 --> 00:52:05.290
And you can imagine building a
wormhole or something like that

00:52:05.290 --> 00:52:06.860
that would get into the past.

00:52:06.860 --> 00:52:08.610
And remember I said
just a few slides ago

00:52:08.610 --> 00:52:11.680
that our impression that
there is free will and choice

00:52:11.680 --> 00:52:15.660
is ultimately because entropy
is increasing toward the future.

00:52:15.660 --> 00:52:18.740
So if you were able to hop in a
wormhole like an "Interstellar"

00:52:18.740 --> 00:52:22.980
and go into the past,
then your personal future

00:52:22.980 --> 00:52:25.280
would be the past
of the universe.

00:52:25.280 --> 00:52:26.574
And which one wins?

00:52:26.574 --> 00:52:28.240
And that's a very
good question to which

00:52:28.240 --> 00:52:29.406
no one has the right answer.

00:52:29.406 --> 00:52:31.600
Probably the simple
answer is you can't do it,

00:52:31.600 --> 00:52:33.670
you can't go backward in time.

00:52:33.670 --> 00:52:36.220
AUDIENCE: The
emergent properties

00:52:36.220 --> 00:52:39.560
that come out of
atoms or of us, do

00:52:39.560 --> 00:52:40.940
you think they're determined?

00:52:40.940 --> 00:52:43.617
You said they're implicit.

00:52:43.617 --> 00:52:45.200
Do they have to
happen, or could there

00:52:45.200 --> 00:52:48.560
be other emerging properties
from the same particles?

00:52:48.560 --> 00:52:51.997
SEAN CARROLL: Well this
is a good question too.

00:52:51.997 --> 00:52:54.080
Are the emergent properties
determined in some way

00:52:54.080 --> 00:52:56.930
from the underlying stuff?

00:52:56.930 --> 00:52:57.830
Yes and no.

00:52:57.830 --> 00:53:00.180
I mean ultimately the
answer is yes in the sense

00:53:00.180 --> 00:53:02.780
that if you believe
everything I've said,

00:53:02.780 --> 00:53:04.740
then given that Core
Theory equation,

00:53:04.740 --> 00:53:07.202
you could put it on a computer
and uniquely find out what

00:53:07.202 --> 00:53:08.860
would happen in the future.

00:53:08.860 --> 00:53:10.690
So in that sense
everything is determined.

00:53:10.690 --> 00:53:13.300
There's the one
very large footnote

00:53:13.300 --> 00:53:15.240
to that, which is of
course quantum mechanics

00:53:15.240 --> 00:53:17.460
introduces some
uncertainty of the game.

00:53:17.460 --> 00:53:20.160
As I personally am an
advocate of the many worlds

00:53:20.160 --> 00:53:21.840
interpretation where
everything's still

00:53:21.840 --> 00:53:23.970
is 100% deterministic,
but not everyone

00:53:23.970 --> 00:53:25.650
agrees with me about that.

00:53:25.650 --> 00:53:29.640
So that doesn't give you any
help whatsoever in the emergent

00:53:29.640 --> 00:53:30.485
properties business.

00:53:30.485 --> 00:53:31.235
It's still a rule.

00:53:31.235 --> 00:53:33.110
It's just a boring
rule for probabilities

00:53:33.110 --> 00:53:35.280
rather than some
deterministic rule.

00:53:35.280 --> 00:53:37.540
So on the one hand,
if you knew everything

00:53:37.540 --> 00:53:40.210
and had Laplacian demon
level intelligence

00:53:40.210 --> 00:53:42.740
about the underlying stuff,
the future is determined.

00:53:42.740 --> 00:53:44.365
The emergent properties
are determined.

00:53:44.365 --> 00:53:45.620
That's the whole story.

00:53:45.620 --> 00:53:48.820
On the other hand, you
do gain new knowledge

00:53:48.820 --> 00:53:51.730
by figuring out what those
emergent properties are.

00:53:51.730 --> 00:53:53.890
You have a way of talking
about the system that

00:53:53.890 --> 00:53:57.030
is extremely
algorithmically compressed

00:53:57.030 --> 00:53:59.790
compared to the microscopic
way of talking about it.

00:53:59.790 --> 00:54:03.850
So even though the
behavior is determined,

00:54:03.850 --> 00:54:06.480
you do learn something new by
figuring out what the higher

00:54:06.480 --> 00:54:08.220
level laws really are.

00:54:08.220 --> 00:54:11.030
And the higher level
laws could be true even

00:54:11.030 --> 00:54:12.770
with different underlying stuff.

00:54:12.770 --> 00:54:15.190
The underlying stuff determines
the higher level laws,

00:54:15.190 --> 00:54:16.576
but not vice versa.

00:54:19.286 --> 00:54:21.660
The way to become a successful
biologist or psychologists

00:54:21.660 --> 00:54:23.325
is not to study
particle physics.

00:54:23.325 --> 00:54:26.190
That's the
fundamental rule here.

00:54:26.190 --> 00:54:30.670
AUDIENCE: So you said that the
Core Theory sort of explains

00:54:30.670 --> 00:54:34.720
like-- and it will remain
true for forever basically.

00:54:34.720 --> 00:54:39.250
So at different
moments in our history

00:54:39.250 --> 00:54:42.690
we've had this sort
of view of physics

00:54:42.690 --> 00:54:44.340
or mechanics or whatever.

00:54:44.340 --> 00:54:47.750
What makes this moment in
human history different,

00:54:47.750 --> 00:54:50.687
like whatever we know
will never change?

00:54:50.687 --> 00:54:53.020
SEAN CARROLL: Well again,
it's not that whatever we know

00:54:53.020 --> 00:54:53.850
will never change.

00:54:53.850 --> 00:54:56.630
It's that very particular way
of talking about the universe

00:54:56.630 --> 00:54:57.620
will remain accurate.

00:54:57.620 --> 00:55:00.725
Like Newtonian gravity
was well established.

00:55:00.725 --> 00:55:03.170
Of course now we know
that the vocabulary

00:55:03.170 --> 00:55:06.305
used by Newtonian gravity is
not the best vocabulary to use.

00:55:06.305 --> 00:55:08.430
Einstein's theory of general
relativity came along,

00:55:08.430 --> 00:55:11.317
gave us a very good,
better way of talking.

00:55:11.317 --> 00:55:12.900
And the whole
vocabulary is different.

00:55:12.900 --> 00:55:15.940
Einstein talks about curved
space time and energy momentum.

00:55:15.940 --> 00:55:18.450
Newton talks about absolute
space and time and forces

00:55:18.450 --> 00:55:19.750
and so forth.

00:55:19.750 --> 00:55:22.040
But it remains true
that if you want

00:55:22.040 --> 00:55:23.890
to get a rocket from
the Earth to the Moon,

00:55:23.890 --> 00:55:27.320
you put Newton's equations
into the computer.

00:55:27.320 --> 00:55:30.735
So there is a certain
level of establishedness

00:55:30.735 --> 00:55:33.380
that a scientific
theory has passed

00:55:33.380 --> 00:55:37.386
which it might be improved upon,
but it will not be discarded.

00:55:37.386 --> 00:55:39.510
If you're thinking about
things like the phlogiston

00:55:39.510 --> 00:55:43.630
model of combustion or the
plum pudding model of the atom,

00:55:43.630 --> 00:55:46.400
those were never
accepted as correct.

00:55:46.400 --> 00:55:48.007
The Core Theory
is just as likely

00:55:48.007 --> 00:55:50.340
to remain true as this statement
that this table is made

00:55:50.340 --> 00:55:52.469
of atoms is likely to be true.

00:55:52.469 --> 00:55:54.010
You might have a
better understanding

00:55:54.010 --> 00:55:55.877
of what atoms are,
but the table's

00:55:55.877 --> 00:55:57.460
not going to stop
being made of atoms.

00:55:57.460 --> 00:55:59.710
AUDIENCE: What are you
working on these days?

00:55:59.710 --> 00:56:01.040
SEAN CARROLL: What am I
working on these days?

00:56:01.040 --> 00:56:02.880
I'm working on doing
exactly this thing, which

00:56:02.880 --> 00:56:05.460
is making a better version of
the underlying laws of physics.

00:56:08.370 --> 00:56:11.030
We do have this problem that
quantum mechanics and gravity

00:56:11.030 --> 00:56:14.300
do not play well together
in extreme conditions,

00:56:14.300 --> 00:56:16.950
near the Big Bang, near the
black holes and so forth.

00:56:16.950 --> 00:56:18.940
So there are some
of us who think

00:56:18.940 --> 00:56:22.360
that space and time themselves
are not fundamental,

00:56:22.360 --> 00:56:24.760
that we need to do better at
a quantum mechanical level

00:56:24.760 --> 00:56:27.640
of figuring out how space
and time themselves are

00:56:27.640 --> 00:56:30.050
emergent from a deeper
level of description.

00:56:30.050 --> 00:56:34.800
So I actually am
ambivalent about time.

00:56:34.800 --> 00:56:36.820
Time may or may
not be fundamental.

00:56:36.820 --> 00:56:40.670
I'm 99% convinced that
space is not fundamental,

00:56:40.670 --> 00:56:42.529
and it's somehow a
good approximation

00:56:42.529 --> 00:56:44.820
just like the fluid description
of the air this room is

00:56:44.820 --> 00:56:46.940
a good approximation, even
though it's ultimately

00:56:46.940 --> 00:56:48.580
made of atoms.

