Where do we stand
on the evolution

00:57:11.240 --> 00:57:14.225
of statistical mechanics then?

00:57:14.225 --> 00:57:16.350
SEAN CARROLL: You point
our a very important point.

00:57:16.350 --> 00:57:18.980
It's actually related
to the earlier question.

00:57:18.980 --> 00:57:23.940
Statistical mechanics speaks
a language of core screening

00:57:23.940 --> 00:57:25.800
and macroscopic states.

00:57:25.800 --> 00:57:27.570
So if you have a bunch
of air in this room

00:57:27.570 --> 00:57:30.600
like we have right now
and it's made of air atoms

00:57:30.600 --> 00:57:35.270
and molecules, you want to
describe it in a course grained

00:57:35.270 --> 00:57:37.370
way as a fluid
with a temperature

00:57:37.370 --> 00:57:39.120
and a pressure and a density.

00:57:39.120 --> 00:57:41.110
Well that's one way
of describing it.

00:57:41.110 --> 00:57:43.140
That's one sort of
macroscopic description.

00:57:43.140 --> 00:57:44.140
But there are many ways.

00:57:44.140 --> 00:57:45.700
For example when we
really coarse grain,

00:57:45.700 --> 00:57:47.366
we really take a
little region of space,

00:57:47.366 --> 00:57:49.900
like one cubic
millimeter in size.

00:57:49.900 --> 00:57:51.692
We take the average
number of particles

00:57:51.692 --> 00:57:53.400
and the average motion
of those particles

00:57:53.400 --> 00:57:55.490
and we relate them to
macroscopic features

00:57:55.490 --> 00:58:00.160
of temperature and density
and pressure and so forth.

00:58:00.160 --> 00:58:01.660
But who says that's
what you can do?

00:58:01.660 --> 00:58:04.760
You could imagine taking a
little tiny cube in momentum

00:58:04.760 --> 00:58:07.057
space rather than
physical space.

00:58:07.057 --> 00:58:08.390
You could coarse grain that way.

00:58:08.390 --> 00:58:11.060
You could reduce your number
of variables that way.

00:58:11.060 --> 00:58:14.210
What you would end up
getting is a horrendous mess.

00:58:14.210 --> 00:58:17.340
And that's because given the
actual configuration of stuff

00:58:17.340 --> 00:58:20.250
in the world and
the laws of physics,

00:58:20.250 --> 00:58:22.950
there's some
reductions from many,

00:58:22.950 --> 00:58:26.260
many particles to much smaller
macroscopic descriptions that

00:58:26.260 --> 00:58:29.360
work nicely, and
some that don't.

00:58:29.360 --> 00:58:33.110
So even though it in principle
sounds very arbitrary,

00:58:33.110 --> 00:58:36.280
in practice this gain in
knowledge and understanding

00:58:36.280 --> 00:58:38.890
that you get from moving
to the macro level

00:58:38.890 --> 00:58:40.910
is highly, highly constrained.

00:58:40.910 --> 00:58:43.809
We don't know all the details of
how it should work in general.

00:58:43.809 --> 00:58:46.100
It's usually something where
we know it when we see it,

00:58:46.100 --> 00:58:48.010
which is not nearly
satisfying enough.

00:58:48.010 --> 00:58:49.990
We want to do better.

00:58:49.990 --> 00:58:53.950
But there does not seem to
be multiple incompatible

00:58:53.950 --> 00:58:58.080
macroscopic descriptions of
the same realistic underlying

00:58:58.080 --> 00:58:59.080
stuff.

00:58:59.080 --> 00:59:01.057
There might be in
special circumstances,

00:59:01.057 --> 00:59:03.390
but in the real world that
doesn't seem to be a problem.

00:59:03.390 --> 00:59:06.350
So I think there's
an interesting issue

00:59:06.350 --> 00:59:08.350
at the intersection of
philosophy and physics

00:59:08.350 --> 00:59:11.760
here about why that is the case,
but in practice that really

00:59:11.760 --> 00:59:14.075
does seem to be the case.

00:59:14.075 --> 00:59:16.700
AUDIENCE: You spoke a little bit
earlier about the Higgs field,

00:59:16.700 --> 00:59:18.658
and when you excite it
you get the Higgs boson.

00:59:18.658 --> 00:59:21.200
And then you also mentioned
that there might even

00:59:21.200 --> 00:59:24.246
be a new particle
on the horizon as we

00:59:24.246 --> 00:59:25.870
add more and more
energy to the systems

00:59:25.870 --> 00:59:28.210
or simulate our collisions.

00:59:28.210 --> 00:59:31.150
Do you foresee that
we'll just keep

00:59:31.150 --> 00:59:33.571
discovering that there's an
infinite number of particles?

00:59:33.571 --> 00:59:35.820
And actually I have an even
more fundamental question,

00:59:35.820 --> 00:59:39.110
which is what is the meaning
of these particles that

00:59:39.110 --> 00:59:42.007
exist almost for
less than an instant?

00:59:42.007 --> 00:59:42.840
SEAN CARROLL: Right.

00:59:42.840 --> 00:59:44.440
And although these
are good questions,

00:59:44.440 --> 00:59:46.840
I don't think there are an
infinite number of varieties

00:59:46.840 --> 00:59:47.480
of particles.

00:59:47.480 --> 00:59:48.890
This is just my guess.

00:59:48.890 --> 00:59:49.520
What do I know?

00:59:49.520 --> 00:59:51.740
We don't know is the only
correct and humble thing

00:59:51.740 --> 00:59:53.380
to say.

00:59:53.380 --> 00:59:56.175
But I think that given
the existence of gravity,

00:59:56.175 --> 00:59:58.300
you can't have particles
that are infinitely heavy.

00:59:58.300 --> 01:00:00.330
They become black
holes at some point.

01:00:00.330 --> 01:00:01.909
So there's probably
some finiteness

01:00:01.909 --> 01:00:03.950
to a list of all the
different kinds of particles

01:00:03.950 --> 01:00:06.602
we can imagine having.

01:00:06.602 --> 01:00:08.060
Sorry, what was
the other question?

01:00:08.060 --> 01:00:09.765
AUDIENCE: What was
the point of those?

01:00:09.765 --> 01:00:11.130
SEAN CARROLL: Oh, what's
the point of them?

01:00:11.130 --> 01:00:12.360
Oh, they're not a point.

01:00:12.360 --> 01:00:13.280
They're just there.

01:00:13.280 --> 01:00:15.070
Not everything needs
to have a point.

01:00:15.070 --> 01:00:17.045
Things can just be.

01:00:17.045 --> 01:00:19.070
AUDIENCE: And how
can you be so sure

01:00:19.070 --> 01:00:21.570
that those pointless
particles don't

01:00:21.570 --> 01:00:23.649
have a point in our
everyday existence?

01:00:23.649 --> 01:00:25.440
SEAN CARROLL: Well,
that's a good question.

01:00:25.440 --> 01:00:27.400
In the six hour
version of this talk

01:00:27.400 --> 01:00:32.180
or in the book that you can
buy right now, I explain why.

01:00:32.180 --> 01:00:34.750
Basically there's different
ways that other particles

01:00:34.750 --> 01:00:35.830
could exist.

01:00:35.830 --> 01:00:38.920
They could be so heavy
that you need a $10 billion

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:41.190
particle accelerator
to make them.

01:00:41.190 --> 01:00:43.690
They could be so short lived
that even if you bring them

01:00:43.690 --> 01:00:46.140
into existence, they
disappear almost instantly.

01:00:46.140 --> 01:00:47.990
Or they could be so
weakly interacting

01:00:47.990 --> 01:00:50.031
that even if they were
there, they would go right

01:00:50.031 --> 01:00:50.800
through your body.

01:00:50.800 --> 01:00:53.300
All these are ways that
particles could have avoided

01:00:53.300 --> 01:00:55.710
detection, but in
every case, they

01:00:55.710 --> 01:00:58.104
will not be interesting or
useful in your everyday life.

01:00:58.104 --> 01:00:59.270
They would not have a point.

01:00:59.270 --> 01:01:03.530
AUDIENCE: But would they have a
point to any important feature

01:01:03.530 --> 01:01:05.721
or fact about the universe?

01:01:05.721 --> 01:01:07.470
SEAN CARROLL: Yeah,
they might play a role

01:01:07.470 --> 01:01:10.080
in sort of understanding how
the different forces of nature

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:12.820
unify at high energies
or something like that.

01:01:12.820 --> 01:01:16.240
But again, the idea
that things have points

01:01:16.240 --> 01:01:18.910
is not part of the
fundamental nature of reality.

01:01:18.910 --> 01:01:23.250
This level of meaning
and purpose and causality

01:01:23.250 --> 01:01:25.121
is a higher level
emergent thing.

01:01:25.121 --> 01:01:26.620
It's not something
we have the right

01:01:26.620 --> 01:01:30.310
to demand from the fundamental
architecture of reality.

01:01:30.310 --> 01:01:32.560
AUDIENCE: You mentioned that
you were somewhat certain

01:01:32.560 --> 01:01:36.200
that space was
not a fundamental.

01:01:36.200 --> 01:01:40.400
What gave you that certainty
or what gave you that evidence?

01:01:40.400 --> 01:01:43.260
SEAN CARROLL: So why do I think
that space is more likely to be

01:01:43.260 --> 01:01:45.640
nonfundamental than time?

01:01:45.640 --> 01:01:48.630
For one thing, quantum
mechanics intrinsically

01:01:48.630 --> 01:01:51.134
treats time and space
very differently.

01:01:51.134 --> 01:01:53.050
The fundamental equation
of quantum mechanics,

01:01:53.050 --> 01:01:55.730
Schrodinger's equation,
has time in it,

01:01:55.730 --> 01:01:58.460
but it doesn't have
space, in general.

01:01:58.460 --> 01:02:01.330
So there's a chance that time
really is fundamental just

01:02:01.330 --> 01:02:02.174
for that reason.

01:02:02.174 --> 01:02:03.590
The Schrodinger
equation might not

01:02:03.590 --> 01:02:05.140
be right, might not be
the right description,

01:02:05.140 --> 01:02:06.950
so that's why we are
still not certain.

01:02:06.950 --> 01:02:08.890
But there's at least
a fighting chance.

01:02:08.890 --> 01:02:12.210
Whereas space is just
obviously not fundamental.

01:02:12.210 --> 01:02:17.130
Space is something where, when
you go from classical mechanics

01:02:17.130 --> 01:02:20.532
to quantum mechanics, space
more or less disappears.

01:02:20.532 --> 01:02:21.990
In classical
mechanics, what do you

01:02:21.990 --> 01:02:23.770
have-- some particles
moving through space

01:02:23.770 --> 01:02:25.294
with some velocity.

01:02:25.294 --> 01:02:27.210
In quantum mechanics,
you have a wave function

01:02:27.210 --> 01:02:28.480
of all those particles.

01:02:28.480 --> 01:02:31.310
And that wave function,
we tend to talk a language

01:02:31.310 --> 01:02:34.660
that the wave function is a
function of all the particles

01:02:34.660 --> 01:02:36.700
in their locations in space.

01:02:36.700 --> 01:02:39.540
But we don't have to
talk that language.

01:02:39.540 --> 01:02:42.134
We can use what is called the
momentum space description.

01:02:42.134 --> 01:02:43.800
We can completely
describe the particles

01:02:43.800 --> 01:02:45.591
by how fast they're
moving instead of where

01:02:45.591 --> 01:02:46.950
they are in the universe.

01:02:46.950 --> 01:02:48.366
And for that matter,
we don't need

01:02:48.366 --> 01:02:49.840
to use any description at all.

01:02:49.840 --> 01:02:52.460
We can just use these
quantum mechanical states

01:02:52.460 --> 01:02:56.570
in their own right, with no
reference to space whatsoever.

01:02:56.570 --> 01:02:58.550
So the kind of thing
I'm doing right now

01:02:58.550 --> 01:03:01.530
is trying to figure out ways
to answer the question, someone

01:03:01.530 --> 01:03:05.390
hands you a wave function,
the quantum mechanical state.

01:03:05.390 --> 01:03:07.995
Can you figure out
what it is describing

01:03:07.995 --> 01:03:10.880
at the classical level,
how many particles moving,

01:03:10.880 --> 01:03:13.071
what kind of dimensional
space, et cetera?

01:03:13.071 --> 01:03:15.320
So everything we know about
quantum mechanics, quantum

01:03:15.320 --> 01:03:17.051
gravity, et cetera,
denigrates space

01:03:17.051 --> 01:03:19.050
into something that is
just a good approximation

01:03:19.050 --> 01:03:19.901
of low energies.

01:03:20.050 --> 01:03:20.550
Thank you.

01:03:20.550 --> 01:03:22.100
[INAUDIBLE]

